My parents sued me for starting a business without putting their names on the paperwork. Last year I launched a cleaning company after saving 15 k working 3 jobs. My reward, a lawsuit from my own parents and 50% ownership because we raised you so we own half your success. I've been grinding since 16, worked through college, paid my own tuition, lived in a basement apartment with 2 roommates, never asked for help. Meanwhile, my brother Marcus got everything handed to him. They bankrolled his failed food truck venture that lasted 6 months, covered his crypto losses when he dropped 20 k on some scam coin, even paid his UI lawyer twice. When he moved back home at 28 with no job and no plan, they remodeled the entire basement for him. New carpet, fresh paint, gaming setup included. When my business hit 200 k revenue in year 1, suddenly I became the villain. Their lawyer sent a certified letter demanding I add them as co owners with full profit sharing rights, give Marcus a management position at 80 k annual salary despite zero experience and pay 30 k in emotional damages for excluding family from my success. I laughed and filed it in my trash folder. That's when the real harassment started. Mom posted on Facebook, some children forget who sacrificed for them. Success should be shared with family not hoarded. Disappointed in the values we apparently failed to teach. Within hours, relatives I hadn't seen in years. Were commenting. Marcus wrote, greed ruins people. Family means nothing anymore, I guess. My aunt started a group chat with 47 family members titled The Situation where everyone discussed my cousins who never worked a day in their lives were suddenly experts on business ethics and family loyalty. My grandmother called crying saying I was breaking her heart and tearing the family apart. Dad started showing up at my client site telling business owners I was unstable and unreliable. One client actually called to verify mom sent emails to my entire contact list claiming I'd stolen the business idea from Marcus and owed him compensation. Marcus posted Instagram Stories outside my apartment talking about how blood means nothing to some people. They actually hired a lawyer and filed court dates set for three months out. I spent those months collecting evidence, every single piece of documentation I could find. They arrives. They showed up with Marcus, my aunt and two cousins for moral support, all wearing matching navy suits like they coordinated a family uniform. Mom carried a photo album. Dad had a folder 2 inches thick. Their lawyer clearly uncomfortable, began presenting evidence. Childhood photos of me opening birthday presents, family vacation pictures from 2008, even my kindergarten graduation program. They created an itemized spreadsheet of every expense. Races, 40 $200. Little League, $800. Summer camp, 40 five hundred dollars. School supplies, 20. Three hundred dollars. Car insurance when I was 17, 1 $800. 23 years of receipts totaling $67,000. Mom testify I that starting a business without including family was a betrayal of everything we taught him about loyalty. Dad claimed he'd given me valuable advice at dinner once that directly LED to my success. Therefore, he deserved equity.
NA

My competitive friend was always insulting my wine, so I tricked him into sampling and insulting his own. So during the pandemic I got really into making wine. Like, really into it. Before that I hadn't touched brewing in maybe 15 years. But when we all got locked down and the one decent liquor store we could get to close for like a year straight, I figured why not start up again? I had the time and honestly everyone was going crazy without anything to drink. Started small with some basic fruit wines using whatever I could find locally. Apples, berries, anything that would ferment. Pretty soon I was making mead too, and even figured out how to malt grain to make beer since the nearest homebrew shop was literally thousands of miles away. Yeah, we lived in a weird spot. Anyway, my stuff turned out pretty decent. Clear, balanced, strong enough to get the job done. Nothing fancy, but it worked. Word got around fast because nobody had any other options. People started trading me things for bottles. my neighbor gave me fresh eggs every week for a case of apple wine. Another guy fixed my fence for some mead. It was honestly a pretty sweet setup and kept everyone happy during a really boring time. But this one guy in our group, let's call him Brian, absolutely hated that I was doing this. He made wine too, but his was honestly not great. It was drinkable. I Guess, but nothing special. The thing that really got under his skin was that people actually wanted mine. At parties, everyone would drink my stuff and his bottles would just sit there mostly untouched. His wife would always try to hype up his wine, too, which made it even more awkward. Brian started making comments every single time we hung out. If I brought wine to someone's house, he'd make a face and say something like, oh, you brought the battery acid? Or trying to poison us again, huh? At first I laughed it off because whatever, dude, more for everyone else. But he kept going. Every gathering, every tasting night, every time someone mentioned my wine, he had something negative to say. His wife backed him up too, which I thought was weird. Like she'd agree and say things like, yeah, Brian's wine is so much smoother, even when she'd barely touched his own bottles. Did faking sick to skip school go too far? I used to fake sick at least once a month. Nothing dramatic, just your classic ugh, my stomach hurts routine. I'd shuffle into the kitchen, wrap myself in a blanket, throw in a little cough, and wait for my mom to sigh and say, fine, but no video games. She always fell for it. Or maybe she just didn't care enough to argue. This time felt no different. It was a Thursday. I had a math test I wasn't ready for, and zero energy to sit through Mr. Danner's forty five minute rant about fractions, so I pulled out the old stomachache move. My mom was already halfway out the door for work, so she just nodded and left. I grabbed a bowl of cereal, flopped on to the couch, and turned on some cartoons, already feeling like I'd won. Dad works nights, so he usually sleeps through most of the day and the house stays quiet, but around 10:00 I heard his door open. I muted the TV and listened. He walked past the living room without noticing me, phone in hand, and stepped out into the garage. Didn't think much of it at first, figured maybe he was calling in sick or trying to get a refund for something. But then I heard his voice through the wall. And it wasn't his normal voice. It was quiet, tired, flat. I can't do this anymore, he said. I paused. I Tried. I really tried. But I feel like I don't even know my family anymore. I come home and everything's just cold. I tiptoed down the hall, heart suddenly racing. The garage door was cracked open, just like always, and I crouched beside it. I know this isn't what we wanted, but it's where we are now, he said. Every day I feel like I'm just pretending. Pretending to be fine. Pretending to be a good husband, a good dad. My stomach twisted. This time for real. I mean, look at him, he said. He doesn't even like me. He doesn't talk to me unless he wants something. And when he does, it's just one word. Answers. I don't even know who he is anymore. My throat went dry. I look at him and all I can think is, what happened? What did I do wrong? When did he start looking at me like I was a stranger? There was silence then. I know it's awful, but sometimes I wonder if I'd be happier alone. Just starting over. Somewhere quiet. Somewhere nobody knows me. My chest felt like it caved in. I haven't said anything to her yet, he continued. I don't even know if I will. But I can't keep going like this. I'm exhausted. I backed away from the door before I could hear more. I stumbled into the bathroom and locked the door behind me, sat on the edge of the tub and stared at the floor. He didn't know I was home. He didn't know I was listening. And he definitely didn't know I had just realized something I could never unhear. My dad didn't just feel lost. He felt lost because of me. I stayed in the bathroom for over an hour, just trying to breathe. When I finally came out, he was back in his room. I crept into mine, got under the covers, and didn't move for the rest the day. Later that night, he knocked on my door. How's your stomach? He asked. Fine. I mumbled. Need anything? No. He stood there for a second longer, then said, okay, let me know. I said nothing.

One Saturday, I was helping my dad clean out the garage. We were sorting through old tools and junk when I saw this spare Key hanging on a little hook. It had a label that said Pete in my dad's handwriting. That made zero sense to me. Pete didn't live with us. He had his own apartment across town. Why would he need a key to our house? When I asked my dad about it, he just chuckled and said Pete probably made a copy years ago when they used to share tools back and forth. You know how your uncle is always borrowing something, dad said. But something about that explanation felt wrong. Pete hadn't borrowed tools in years. That night I couldn't sleep. Something about that key kept bugging me. Why would Pete still need access to our house? Why was the key hanging in the garage where everyone could see it? The more I thought about it, the weirder it seemed. The next day I decided to fake being sick and stay home from school. I told my mom I had a headache and she believed me. After everyone left for work and school, I just waited. I had this gut feeling that something was going to happen. Around two forty five PM, right before Emily usually walked home from school and stopped by our house to wait for her mom to pick her up. I heard the garage door open, but nobody was supposed to be home. I looked out the window and saw Pete's blue Honda pulling into our driveway. My heart started pounding. Pete walked straight into the Garage like he owned the place. Grab that key and let himself into the house through the side door. He didn't even knock or call out to see if anyone was home. He just walked right in. I followed him from upstairs, trying to be as quiet as possible. He went straight to the downstairs guest room where Emily usually waited. When she came over, Pete looked around then.

Ma, honey, let's go play on the slides, I whispered, trying to drag her away from the wedding party, but she wasn't having it. She broke free from my grip and marched right up to the bride, tugging on her dress. Lady, don't marry the mean man, Emma said, pointing directly at the groom. He's gonna hurt you. Everyone went dead silent. The groom's face went red and he started walking toward us looking angry. Hey, what kind of kid says something like that? What are you teaching her? I started apologizing, explaining that Emma was just 3 and had an active imagination. But then the bride knelt down to Emma's level and asked quietly, sweetie, why do you think he's mean? Emma pointed to a bruise on the bride's wrist that was barely covered by her dress sleeve. My mommy had marks like that when the bad man lived with us. She cried at night, too, just like you smell like tears under your makeup. My heart stopped. This kid had been through way too much for her age, but she developed This weird ability to spot things adults tried to hide. When my ex was still around, Emma would always know when I'd been crying, even if I thought I'd covered it up perfectly.

Are you. Are you alive? Yeah, bro. I just had the worst couple days of my life. What? Why? What happened? You know that new diet I've been on, right? Uh, yeah. I heard that eating fiber helps you lose weight. So I got five boxes of those fiber one bars. That's all I've been eating. Nothing else? Just fiber bars. I couldn't the day after that. I did the same thing. I ate six more boxes of fiber bars. Only I didn't that day, either. I was getting very worried. I take at least one on a normal day, but I could feel the fat burning off my body from all the fiber. I didn't the day after that, either. I didn't the fourth day. I didn't the fifth day. I didn't the sixth day. But then I was drinking my morning coffee, and I started hearing the loudest rumble I've ever heard. I thought it was an earthquake or volcano exploding, but no, it was my stomach. I rushed to the toilet. The moment my. Hits the toilet, the loudest and most funkiest fart comes out of my. It took eight seconds for the fart to finish. My mom rushed to the bathroom door. She thought something happened to me. Then it stops. A brick starts to come out, and it's so solid that I feel like I'm giving birth to Megamind out of my. I hung on to the shower curtain and I prayed. I ripped the Whole shower curtain out of the wall. Then the brick finally came out at speeds faster than a F1 racing car. The entire bathroom was soaking in toilet water. That's just the start. A fart that could do more damage than a nuclear missile starts a barrage of bullets from me. After an hour, it seemed to be over. I'm crying at this point, and I can barely breathe. I wipe my butt crystal clean. What the actual

My wife and friends laughed while making rules for me. I made one rule that silenced them all. Mocking laughter hit me before I opened the door. I walked in to find five women in a circle with notebooks on my coffee table, all red faced from laughing. My wife held a handwritten list. And No. 12, she announced between giggles, he has to ask permission before buying anything over $20. The group erupted. One woman slapped her knee. Oh, look, speak of the devil, one friend chirped. We were just discussing you, my wife beamed. We're making rules that would make marriages better, guidelines for husbands to follow. These weren't suggestions. These were commands wrapped in female empowerment. What kind of rules? I asked calmly. They rattled off their masterpiece. Rule 1, all major decisions require wife approval. Rule 7, daily gratitude. Speeches about his wife, minimum two minutes. Rule 11, no single friends. They give ideas about freedom. Rule 18, the notebook woman read, weekly allowance system, spending money based on rule compliance. Good behavior rewarded, bad behavior punished. They discussed me like a child needing behavioral modification while I sat 3 feet away. How would you enforce these? I asked conversationally. They eagerly shared strategies, withholding privileges, public embarrassment, financial consequences. My wife nodded, if he's stubborn, we use social pressure. Get other wives involved. Community effort. That's brilliant, I said. Meaning it, they'd revealed how little they respected any man in their orbit. Before we continue, If I'm subject to 18 rules without input, I, I should contribute one rule of my own. Silence. I was supposed to passively receive their wisdom, not participate. What kind of rule? My wife asked cautiously. One simple rule for balance and fairness they couldn't refuse without admitting their system was one sided. Fine, my wife said. One rule. I stood slowly. Any woman creating rules to control her husband automatically declares herself available for the same treatment from other men. Complete silence. What does that mean, my wife asked. Confidence gone. By establishing that spouses can unilaterally create binding rules, you've opened the door for reciprocal treatment. If you can make rules for me, I can make rules for you. That's not the same thing, one protested, isn't it? You explained how husbands need structure and oversight. I'm applying that logic to wives who redesign marriages.

She said, my friends and I are using your lake house this weekend. Don't be weird about it. After trashing my apartment last week, I replied, have fun. Then I called the property management and canceled her access code. Chloe was my roommate for eight months. The first few months were fine, but then she started treating our apartment like her personal party venue. Last weekend was the final straw. I was visiting my parents and came back to find my apartment destroyed. Red wine stains on my couch, cigarette burns on my coffee table, broken glass everywhere, vomit in my bathtub, and my bedroom door kicked in. Security footage showed Chloe letting in 15 people Saturday night. When I confronted her, she shrugged and said, don't be so uptight. It was just a party. I'll Venmo you for the door. I gave her 30 days notice. She moved out Wednesday without cleaning or paying for damages. Then Thursday, I got this text. Hey, me and my girls are using your lake house this weekend for Jasmine's birthday. We'll be there Friday Sunday. Don't be weird about it. My family has a lake house that Chloe knew about because I brought her there once. What she didn't know was that it belongs to my uncle and uses a property management company with access codes. I texted back, have fun, then immediately called the company, explained someone I no longer trusted had my code, and they deactivated it instantly. Friday around 6 p m, my phone exploded. 17 missed calls from Chloe. Texts flooding in. The code isn't working. We drove two hours. You need to call the property people. I didn't respond. Went to see a movie instead. Company has security cameras at the gate. My uncle forwarded me the footage. Chloe's SUV pulled up at five forty three PM Friday. They tried the code multiple times. One girl got out screaming at the keypad. They sat there for three hours unloading coolers. Two of them tried to climb the 8 foot fence with pointed tops. Finally, around 9 p m, they gave up and drove away. Everything was booked due to a local festival, so they drove back home Friday night. The texts kept coming all weekend. Saturday morning. You ruined my birthday weekend. We all took time off work for this. How can you be such an awful person? I responded, I'm not sure what you're talking about. Chloe told me you were using my lake house. But I don't own any property. Maybe she was confused. Chloe went from threatening to sue me to calling me pathetic, to saying I owed her money for gas, finally admitting she never had permission. But I shouldn't be such a dick about it because normal people share. But it gets better. All week, someone had been calling the property company claiming to be various people. My sister, girlfriend, business partner, trying to get access. The final straw was claiming there Was an emergency, and she needed to

My parents ignored my birthday again, but when they saw my 94 thousand dollar Mercedes on Instagram, my dad called. Where did you get the money? Family meeting tomorrow. Six PM they had no idea what was coming. I'm Marcus, 26, and I've been the invisible son for years. While my parents throw Celebration parties every time my younger sister Emma gets a participation trophy in her dance classes, I quietly became the youngest regional sales director at a tech startup making serious money. The favoritism has been absolutely insane my entire life. When Emma wanted to try violin at 15, they bought her a 2 thousand dollar instrument without hesitation. When I asked for help with college textbook, dad literally handed me a McDonald's application and said, earn it yourself. When she decided violin wasn't for her and wanted to switch to dance, they enrolled her in the most expensive studio in town, paying 400 dollar monthly without blinking. Last month was the absolute final straw. Emma announced she's switching from dance to pottery because she found her true artistic calling. My parents immediately offered to fund a 3,000 dollar pottery wheel Kiln and complete studio setup. Mom was so excited she started researching pottery classes that same night, already planning Emma's artistic future. Meanwhile, I've been living off ramen noodles and sleeping on a mattress on the floor because they told me at 26 I should figure out my own finances and stop being a burden on the Family. When I asked for a small loan to help with a security deposit on a better apartment, dad gave me a 45 minute lecture about fiscal responsibility. The irony, while they were treating me like a complete financial liability, been quietly crushing it at work. Three months ago, I closed the biggest software integration deal in our company's entire history. A Fortune 500 clients signed a three year contract worth two point eight million dollars and my commission structure meant serious money was finally coming my way. That's when I got my quarterly commission check, $47,000 after taxes from that one deal alone, plus my regular salary and performance bonuses. Instead of being smart and investing it responsibly, I decided to make a statement that would completely shatter their perception of my life. I walked straight into the Mercedes dealership that afternoon. The AMG C63 s was sitting in the showroom like Automo.

My girlfriend laughed and said, what are you going to do, break up with me? After I caught her texting her ex. I didn't say a word, just walked to the bedroom and started packing. She kept laughing from the couch. You're being dramatic, Michael. It's just texting. I pulled out my laptop, opened my banking app and started clicking. Her laughter died when she heard the notification sounds. What are you doing? Still silent. Removed her from my car insurance, canceled her phone plan that I paid for. Click. Change the Netflix password she used daily. Michael, stop. This isn't funny anymore. But I wasn't done. Logged into our shared Spotify account, change the password. Then Amazon Prime, then Hulu, then Disney plus. Every single subscription she used but never paid for. Even changed the Wi Fi password on our router. Are you seriously going through every account right now? Next, I opened my credit card app, removed her as an authorized user. Then my gym membership, cancelled her guest privileges. My Costco card revoked her access. This is insane. You're being psychotic. I grabbed my suitcase and headed for the door. She jumped up. Panic setting in. Wait, where are you going? You can't just leave. Finally spoke. You asked what I was going to do. I'm showing you. My phone buzzed. Uber outside. Michael, I'm sorry. It meant nothing. Then neither does this. I walked out. The Uber driver was cool, helped me load my stuff without Asking questions. We drove away. I saw her standing in the doorway still holding her dead phone, realizing she couldn't even connect to Wi Fi to call for help. 20 minutes later, my phone exploded. Her number was already disconnected since I'd cancelled the plan. But her friends started texting me. She's crying at Starbucks because she can't call an Uber without her phone plan. She tried to drive home but remembered you took her off insurance. She's asking everyone for Netflix passwords because she was watching a show. She went to the gym and they wouldn't let her in. Then came the really good stuff. Her sister called me. Michael, what did you do? Madison's at my place having a complete meltdown. I did exactly what she suggested. She says you cut off everything, her phone, insurance, streaming accounts, gym access. That's petty. Petty is texting your ex behind your boyfriend's back for two months. Two months, she said. It just started. I sent her sister a screenshot of the oldest text I'd found from March. It was now may. Oh, my God, Michael, I'm so sorry. I had no idea. Her sister called back an hour later. She's been lying to everyone. I read through more of those texts. She was planning to leave you, I know, right after her ex said he wasn't ready for a relationship. So you were her backup plan. Exactly. Keep me around for bills while pursuing him emotionally. The next day I. Got a call from an unknown number. Madison using her mom's phone. Michael, please, I.

My sister said everything I cooked would kill her. So I cooked up something that made her want to die. My sister Meredith discovered the perfect scam when she was 12 years old. She Learned that faking allergies got her whatever she wanted. The first time it happened was at a birthday party. She didn't like the chocolate cake, so she told everyone she was allergic to cocoa. Boom, special vanilla cupcake just for her. By high school, she carried a list of 37 fake allergies, gluten, dairy, shellfish, nuts, red dye, MSG, you name it, she was dying from it. Parents change everything for Meredith's medical needs, special meals, special shopping trips, special everything. Meanwhile, I'd catch her sneaking pizza in her room at midnight, the same pizza that would kill her at dinner. When I got into culinary school, Meredith suddenly couldn't breathe around cooking oil. She'd walk by the kitchen and fall on the floor gasping. Mom made me practice cooking in the garage because Meredith's life was at risk. Opening my food truck should have been the best day of my life. Three years of saving every penny I had. Went into Nora's kitchen first day, lunch rush. There's Meredith. She ordered a salad, took one bite and threw herself on the ground. She was rolling around screaming that I poisoned her, clutching her throat, fake tears, full show. Someone called 9, 1 1. She told the paramedics I put gluten in her food on purpose. The hospital photos went everywhere. Online. My Yelp page got destroyed. People called me a murderer. I had to close for a week, lost thousands in sales. I finally saved enough to open a real restaurant. She did it again. Soft opening night. The place was packed with food critics and investors. Meredith touched a shrimp and went into fake shock. She was thashing on the floor. Her boyfriend, Caleb pretended to give her CPR. Everyone was filming. The health department shut me down the next day. My parents believed every lie. Dad said I should have been more careful. Mom banned me from Sunday dinners because my clothes might have bits of food on them. They spent thousands on fake EP pens while I was drowning in debt. Then came my biggest chance ever. Food Network called. They wanted me for their new show, Rising Star Chefs. Ten years of work LED to this moment. This was everything. Three hours before filming, Meredith called the producers, told them I sent her to the hospital at Thanksgiving by getting food on her plate. She sent fake medical records and to sue. They dropped me instantly. Too much risk, they said. That's when I snapped. Meredith was going to learn what real fear felt like. See, while Meredith faked being scared of food, she had one real fear, mice. Found one in her dollhouse at age 8 and never got over it. Just hearing a squeak made her panic. I started Recording her at her boyfriend's place got weeks of footage. Meredith eating pizza with extra cheese, shrimp with peanut sauce, everything that would supposedly kill her. She was having a feast while ruining my life. I bought 50 mice from a pet store, told them I had hungry snakes. Also bought jars of peanut butter, her deadliest allergy. I texted Meredith about making up over lunch, picked a restaurant across town that specialized in allergy free food. She loved the attention, posted photos about forgiving her sister while she was gone.

What became so popular at your school that the teachers had to ban it? At my school, we created snitch lottery that spiraled into madness. My friend got accused of cheating by this girl who tattled on everyone. We were sick of it. I suggested putting fake confessions in the anonymous tip box. Nothing harmful, just ridiculous things like I'm replacing cafeteria salt with sugar or I'm hiding all the markers. Each Friday when the principal read concerns, we'd silently celebrate. Soon, our whole group was making confessions more outlandish. Each week, word spread and half the school will join. Kids bet on which confession would make assembly. Teams formed to create believable yet impossible scenarios. Things went nuclear when someone confessed to breeding raccoons in the ceiling. The principal called animal control who searched all day. While we tried not to lose it, teachers became paranoid looking for rule breakers who didn't exist. The counselor held meetings about the uptick and bizarre behaviour. The breaking point came when someone wrote about laxatives and faculty coffee. Though it never happened, five teachers called in sick. Next day they traced the handwriting and caught a senior. The principal was livid. They removed the tip box and threatened suspension for fabricating safety concerns. Snitch Lottery died that day, but for two months, we made our boring school believe it was losing its mind.

What's the scariest call you got from school? Girl, when I tell you, I almost fainted when the school called me. I ain't even playing. So it's a regular Thursday. I'm in the middle of target looking for a throw pillow that matches absolutely nothing. And my phone rings. Caller ID says Lincoln Elementary. My stomach drop. I thought, oh, god, did she fall off the monkey bars again? Did she hit someone? Or worse, did she say something? Think she heard me say? So I answer all fake sweet, like, hi, this is her mom. And the lady on the other end says, ma'am, we need you to come in immediately. Your daughter had an incident. Now listen, my daughter Layla is cute, like real cute. Big eyes, big hair, big attitude. She's 8, but she's also part gremlin when she's hungry or bored. So I throw the pillows back, leave the car and speed down to that school like it's the Indie 500. I walk in, heart pounding, and the secretary just points at the principal's office like, yeah, she's in there. I open the door and baby Layla is sitting there with her arms crossed like a little mob boss. Principal looking nervous. There's a boy across from her with an ice pack on his head and a teacher looking like she aged 10 years today. I go, Layla, what did you do? She goes, he tried to take my cookie. So I defended myself. Calm like She's in court. The principal sighs and says she hit him with a lunch tray. I blinked. I'm sorry. She what? Now the teacher jumps in. She told the boy, touch it and you lose a finger. We thought she was joking. Next thing we know, he grabs her cookie and boom, metal tray to the forehead. I had to bite the inside of my cheek to keep from laughing because I know where she got that line, me. She got it from me. I said that last week about my fries at Chili's. But I clear my throat and say, Layla, you can't go around hitting people. He goes, he tried to rob me. What was I supposed to do care? Like it's a fairy tale. That cookie had my name on it in Sharpie. I wrote it. Possession is 9/10 of the law, y'all. She hit him with legal terms. The boy starts sniffling like he's the victim here. And Layla leans in and says, you should have asked. Now look at you. I stocked up like leftovers. I had to turn around and pretend to cough so I wouldn't laugh. I'm dying inside. The principal says, we don't condone violence. Layla goes, neither do I, but I condone consequences. I swear, this child is either gonna be a lawyer or in jail. So I take her home, try to give her a serious talk. I go, he can't be violent. Even if you're right, there's rules. She Goes exactly rule No. 1, don't touch my food. I said, Layla, I'm serious. She goes, okay, okay. Next time I'll use words. Maybe. Probably. And then y'all ready for the kicker? That night, I get a text from the mom of the boy. I'm bracing myself.

Neighborhood crackhead lunged at me so I turned him into a femboy and sold him on Etsy. I live in a sketchy little neighborhood where everyone minds their business except for this one dude. Let's call him Rico. Rico is, well, he's like a local cryptid. No one knows where he lives but he appears at 3:00am yelling about government conspiracies, anime girls and how he once fought a raccoon with his bare hands. Classic Rico. Anyway, last night I'm walking back from the corner store with a bag of Hot Cheetos and chocolate milk living my best trashy life when out of nowhere Rico lunges at me like a feral possum in heat. He's screaming something about me stealing his aura. At this point my fight or flight kicked in and apparently my brain chose black magic. See, I've been dabbling in some alternative arts lately. Long story short, I had a transformation Hex saved on my notes app. Don't ask why, just accept it. So mid lunch I screamed the words, clap my hands together and suddenly poof, Rico is no longer Rico. Rico is now Rianna. Pink crop top, cat ears, thigh high socks, eyeliner sharper than my credit score, the full Femboy starter pack. He blinks, I blink. We both stand there for a solid five seconds like, did that just happen? Fast forward to today and uh, I may have listed him on Etsy under Handcrafted Chaos Beings. Someone from Portland bought him within 3 Minutes for 275 plus shipping. Now I'm sitting here sipping my chocolate milk, trying to process the fact that I may have invented a new side hustle. Before anyone asks, yes, Rico. Now Rianna is thriving. The buyer sent me pics. He's got a made outfit. Now I don't know how to feel.

While I was using the toilet at school, a girl in the next stall asked, can you hop over in here? I need extra hands. Yeah, I don't think so. I wasn't about to climb into a bathroom stall with a freak. No, please. I think I might bleed out. Her voice was shaking. And suddenly this wasn't funny anymore. It was summer from my English class, a pregnant senior who everyone whispered about but nobody really talked to. She was sitting on the toilet, gripping the handicap rail with white knuckles, and her face was covered in sweat. What's wrong? I asked, even though I was starting to guess. Please do something. I'm giving birth. She looked up at me with pure terror in her eyes. My whole body went cold. I was 17 and barely knew how tampons worked, let alone babies. But she was crying and alone, and I couldn't just leave her there. I hopped over the stall divider awkwardly and almost slipped on the wet floor. That's when I saw it. The baby was already crowning. There was blood on the toilet seat and the floor, and summer was making the low groaning sounds that scared me more than anything. This was actually happening in a gross school bathroom with fluorescent lights and graffiti on the walls. I'll be right back. I ran out of the bathroom. Still in shock. I sprinted down the hallway to Missus Bashar's classroom. She was my favourite teacher and The only adult I could think of who wouldn't freak out, I burst through her door, interrupting her lecture on photosynthesis. The whole class stared at me. I need your help urgently, please. I was out of breath and probably looked insane. Missus Bashar took one look at my face and followed me without asking questions. We ran back to the bathroom and I could hear summer sounds getting louder. Other kids were starting to peek out of classrooms wondering what was happening. Missus Bashar pushed open the stall door and immediately went into teacher mode. Okay, honey, I'm here. You're doing great. I'm going to support you while she gets the nurse. I didn't need to be told twice. I ran to the nurse's office faster than I'd ever run in PE. When I burst through the door, Nurse Patty was checking Casey's temperature. Casey, who everyone knew was Summer's boyfriend, the guy who'd been bragging about becoming a dad at prom. Summer's having her baby in the bathroom right now. I basically screamed it. Casey's face went from white to green. He threw up all over the floor before Nurse Patty could grab a trash can. But we didn't have time to deal with that. The three of us ran back to the bathroom with nurse Patty grabbing emergency supplies from her cabinet. By now, half the school had heard something was happening. Kids were crowding outside the bathroom door trying to figure out what all the screaming Was about teachers were trying to move them back to class, but nobody was listening. When we got back to the stall, it was chaos. Missus Bashar was holding Summer's hand while she pushed. The nurse immediately took over, checking how dilated she was and telling summer to breathe. Casey stood frozen in the doorway looking like he might pass out. That's when summer grabbed my hand and pulled me close. You have to get.

voice_to_text: They're busy. Last Tuesday, I tried talking to Emma. I made her favorite pasta and waited until she came down for a snack. I said, can we just talk for five minutes? She grabbed an apple and said, there's nothing to talk about. You're destroying our family over something that happened before I could even walk. That's on you. I started crying and she just walked away. Grace won't even look at me. She literally turns her head when I enter a room. Steve keeps texting me saying maybe we should try harder in therapy, that the girls need us together, but I can't do it. Every time I see him, I feel sick. We bought our house in 2003 and it's worth four times what we paid. So we'll both have good places after we sell. The girls won't be living in some dump, but they act like I'm making them homeless. Last week, both girls sat me down, which was the first time they'd spoken to me in days. Emma did most of the talking. She said, if I file the divorce papers, they're done with me forever. Grace nodded and said, we already decided. It's your choice. I looked at both of them and felt my heart actually breaking. These are my babies. I grew them inside me. I stayed up all night when they were sick. I taught them to read and ride bikes, and they're choosing the man who betrayed me. I said, I love You both more than anything. But I can't stay with your father. I'm moving forward with the separation. Emma stood up and said, then we're done here. They both went upstairs. That was 6 days ago. I wasn't about to climb into a bathroom stall with a freak. No, please. I think I might bleed out. Her voice was shaking. And suddenly this wasn't funny anymore. It was summer from my English class, a pregnant senior who everyone whispered about but nobody really talked to. She was sitting on the toilet, gripping the handicap rail with white knuckles, and her face was covered in sweat. What's wrong? I asked, even though I was starting to guess. Please do something. I'm giving birth. She looked up at me with pure terror in her eyes. My whole body went cold. I was 17 and barely knew how tampons worked, let alone babies. But she was crying and alone, and I couldn't just leave her there. I hopped over the stall divider awkwardly and almost slipped on the wet floor. That's when I saw it. The baby was already crowning. There was blood on the toilet seat and the floor, and summer was making the low groaning sounds that scared me more than anything. This was actually happening in a gross school bathroom with fluorescent lights and graffiti on the walls. I'll be right back. I ran out of the bathroom. Still in shock. I sprinted down the hallway to Missus Bashar's classroom. She was my favourite teacher and The only adult I could think of who wouldn't freak out, I burst through her door, interrupting her lecture on photosynthesis. The whole class stared at me. I need your help urgently, please. I was out of breath and probably looked insane. Missus Bashar took one look at my face and followed me without asking questions. We ran back to the bathroom and I could hear summer sounds getting louder. Other kids were starting to peek out of classrooms wondering what was happening. Missus Bashar pushed open the stall door and immediately went into teacher mode. Okay, honey, I'm here. You're doing great. I'm going to support you while she gets the nurse. I didn't need to be told twice. I ran to the nurse's office faster than I'd ever run in PE. When I burst through the door, Nurse Patty was checking Casey's temperature. Casey, who everyone knew was Summer's boyfriend, the guy who'd been bragging about becoming a dad at prom. Summer's having her baby in the bathroom right now. I basically screamed it. Casey's face went from white to green. He threw up all over the floor before Nurse Patty could grab a trash can. But we didn't have time to deal with that. The three of us ran back to the bathroom with nurse Patty grabbing emergency supplies from her cabinet. By now, half the school had heard something was happening. Kids were crowding outside the bathroom door trying to figure out what all the screaming Was about teachers were trying to move them back to class, but nobody was listening. When we got back to the stall, it was chaos. Missus Bashar was holding Summer's hand while she pushed. The nurse immediately took over, checking how dilated she was and telling summer to breathe. Casey stood frozen in the doorway looking like he might pass out. That's when summer grabbed my hand and pulled me close. You have to get.

voice_to_text: My brother got my fiance pregnant, and my dad gave him the family business and a house. So I decided to make them both pay for their betrayal. I found out on a Tuesday. Sophie called in tears, voice shaking so hard I thought someone had died. She sat in her car outside our house, gripping the steering wheel like she was about to crash it. I'm pregnant, she said. For three seconds, I smiled. We've been talking about kids for months. And she added, it might not be yours. Silence. The air around me turned thick. My throat burned. Who? I asked. But I already knew. Her eyes darted away. It wasn't supposed to. Tell me. It's not Alex. The sound she made wasn't even a word. That was all the answer I needed. I staggered out of the car, knees barely working. She chased me, babbling excuses. Late nights. One mistake. She never meant to hurt me. My ears roared. Three months. Four. She swallowed, nodded. I drove straight to the office. My. My brother was there, smug as ever, wearing new Cologne like a cheap disguise. When he saw my face, he knew. Listen, bro, I can explain. My fist landed before the sentence finished. Blood shot from his nose. The room filled with the metallic smell of it, sharp and sour. Dad and two employees pulled me off. Alex shrieked like a coward. She came on to me. We're in love. Those words echoed in the Walls like poison. Mom pressed her hands to her mouth. Janet, our receptionist for 15 years, grabbed her purse and walked out without a word. That silence said more than anything. Dad raised his hands like a judge calling order. His voice was heavy but calm in that fake way he always used when he thought he was the only adult in the room. We'll handle this like adults. Alex spat blood onto the floor, then grinned through it. Teeth red. She's having my baby. You can't ignore that. The room spun. I looked at dad, he looked at Alex, then at me. We'll figure this out. Family is family. I left a week later.

voice_to_text: My new manager fired me in front of the entire restaurant. But Karma served him something he couldn't swallow. Carlos showed up at Rose's Cantina in February with his restaurant management certificate, and right away he started changing everything we've been doing for years. He walked around with a smug attitude, telling everyone the kitchen was disorganized and that we needed to follow modern systems instead of the old ways. After two months of his nonsense, he called me into the main dining room while the whole lunch crew was watching. Miguel, we need to make some changes around here, he announced loud enough for everyone to hear. You refused to follow corporate procedures, so I'm letting you go. You're done. Clear out your things. I've been the head cook at roses for 12 years, and I knew every single regular customer by name and exactly how they like their food. But I just nodded quietly and went to get my stuff. The waitresses all stood there frozen. And Elena, who'd been there almost as long as he, had tears running down her face. As I was walking out with my things, I stopped and said over my shoulder, hope the weekend breakfast rush goes smooth for you. Carlos just waved his hand like it didn't matter. Any trained cook can handle eggs and beans, smiled to myself, Mother's Day weekend is coming up. Should be interesting. His confident expression flickered for just a second. What about Mother's Day? Oh, Nothing special, I said, heading for the door. Just our busiest three days of the year. All the families come in with their special orders. You'll be fine. What Carlos didn't know was that Mother's Day weekend at roses was like the Super Bowl for us. Families would pack the place from Friday through Sunday and every single regular family had their own special way they wanted their breakfast. I've been preparing special seasoned meats for weeks that customers have been asking about, marinating them just right with my own blend of spices I perfected over the years. Carlos had never bothered to learn any of this stuff because he was too busy talking about portion control and standardized recipes. Our customers were families who'd been coming for generations and wanted their food exactly how they remembered it from when their parents brought them as kids. Saturday morning came and at 6:00am sharp, my phone started going off. I ignored it and made myself some coffee. By 6:45, Carlos had called eight times. At 7:15, Elena texted me.

voice_to_text: My girlfriend mocked my cooking until her roommate said, marry him before I do. She suddenly became a food critic. My girlfriend insisted I cook for her roommate's birthday dinner at our apartment. I been planning the menu all week, but she kept reminding me not to go overboard with the fancy stuff, because Lexi preferred simple food. The second I started prepping in the kitchen, setting up my knees on place and heating the cast iron, my girlfriend grabbed her phone and sprawled on the couch. I'm ordering sushi for myself, she announced without looking up. Your food's always too heavy. I watched her scroll through TikTok while I worked on the carbonara from scratch, making fresh pasta and whisking eggs with Eccarino Romano. Smells incredible in here, said a voice from the doorway. Lexi had come home early from work, dark hair pulled back, still in her office clothes, the type who actually appreciated effort when she saw it. Oh, my god, she said, moving closer to the stove. Are you making pasta from scratch? She actually watched me work, not the polite glance people usually give. I didn't know guys our age even knew how to cook like this. My ex could barely make cereal. We started talking about food while I finished the dish. She traveled through Italy last summer. Rome, Florence, Bologna. Real interest, asking about techniques and ingredients. Have you always cooked like this? Lexi asked, leaning against the counter. I'd love to learn Sometime. Your girlfriend is so lucky. My chest tightened. My girlfriend had never once asked to learn anything I made. Not once in two years of dating. I'd even catered her office party last month and she'd introduce the food as something we picked up. Does she eat my food? I asked. Lexi's expression shifted slightly. Well, she mentioned you cook a lot. She paused. Actually, now that I think about it, I've never seen her eat anything you've made. She's always getting take out when we hang out. That hit harder than expected. I cooked five nights a week and ate most meals alone. Lexi must have seen something in my face because she stepped closer. That's her loss. This looks restaurant quality. It's nothing special, I said, plating the carbonara from the living room. I caught my girlfriend glancing over while pretending to watch Netflix.

The kid smiled and asked if he could help be Santa's magic, too. I gave him two candy canes and told him to give one to someone who looked like they needed cheering up. By closing time, word had spread about Steve Claus. The mall manager asked if I could come back tomorrow. Parents were specifically requesting Santa's brother. Brenda offered me $500 for the week. My girlfriend found me still in costume, surrounded by children and took about 50 photos while laughing hysterically. I worked that entire week as claws. Kids would bring drawings of what they imagine the whole claws family look like. One boy brought cookies specifically for me, not Santa. A girl gave me a handmade business card that said assistant to make my job sound more official. On Christmas Eve, my last shift, the original Santa showed up. He'd heard about Steve Claus and came to see what the fuss was about. We took a photo together, told kids we were heading back to help Santa with a big night. The crowd applauded. That mall still has a Steve Claus every year now. It became their thing. I set the precedent, and now some other bearded guy continues the tradition. Last week, a teenager recognized me at a coffee shop. You're the original Steve Claus, he said. Turns out he was Tyler the Kid who exposed me that first day, he said that Christmas was his favorite because he got to be part of creating a new legend.

Children started crying. Brenda looked like she might faint. That's when inspiration struck. I leaned forward and whispered loudly enough for everyone to hear, you're absolutely right, Tyler. I'm not Santa! The crowd gasped. Brenda's face went white, but I continued. I'm Santa's brother, Steve. Santa's busy at the North Pole with a massive toy emergency. A whole shipment of game consoles got delivered to the wrong warehouse. I need to take notes on what everyone wants while he fixes it. Tyler's eyes widened. Santa has a brother? I nodded solemnly. Someone has to run the workshop while he's delivering presents. I usually stay at the North Pole, but this is an emergency. Line of children buzzed with excitement. They'd met Santa's brother. This was even better than regular Santa. For the next three hours, I became Steve Claus. I told kids about my workshop specializing in unusual toys. I explained how I invented the self wrapping present. One girl asked why I wasn't famous like Santa, and I said I preferred working behind the scenes. Some. No one has to test all those video games. I winked. Parents started taking pictures, posting about meeting Santa's mysterious brother. Kids asked increasingly creative questions, and I made up an entire Claus family history. There was Uncle Pete, who trained the reindeer, Cousin Maria, who designed the slay's GPS system, and Grandma Claus, who quality tested all the cookies. Around hour four, a kid with thick glasses approached. My dad says Santa isn't real. He said quietly. The crowd went silent. This was the moment every mall Santa dreaded. I knelt down to his level. Have you ever been recruited to be Santa's helper at a mall by a desperate elf? Last December I was killing time at the mall, waiting for my girlfriend to finish her shift at the jewelry store, when a tiny woman in an elf costume grabbed my arm. you have to help me, she whispered, her fake pointed ears drooping. Santa just quit mid shift and there are 40 kids in line. I'm 6 foot 4 with a beard I've been growing since October. She looked at me like I was the answer to her prayers. I don't know anything about being Santa, I protested. She was already dragging me toward the North Pole setup. Can you say ho ho, ho and not swear in front of children? When I nodded, she said, you're hired. Before I could object, she shoved me into a break room where a red suit hung on a chair, still warm from the previous Santa. He left because the kid threw up on him, she explained, tossing me the pants. Third time this week. I should have run, but she looked so desperate, and somewhere outside, children were waiting. The suit was too small, the jacket barely closed, the pants ended at my calves, and the beard kept sliding sideways. The elf, who introduced herself as Brenda, looked me over and sighed. It'll have to do. Just remember, every kid gets a candy cane, no promises about specific gifts, and absolutely no holding babies. My first kid was easy. A shy five year old who whispered she wanted a Dinosaur. I deepened my voice, said something about checking my list, and sent her off with a candy cane. I thought I had this figured out. Then came Tyler. Tyler was seven, tactical, and armed with questions. Why does your beard smell like coffee? He demanded. How do you fit down chimneys if you're so fat? Before I could answer, he pulled my beard down and announced to the entire line, this isn't the real Santa. Panic spread through the crowd. Parents glared.

What small gesture meant the world to you? When I was 14, I'd already figured out how life worked. You don't expect anything from anyone, and you don't get disappointed. Simple math. My dad left when I was, like, two. I don't even remember his face. My mom was around, technically, but most nights she'd be knocked out on the couch with a bottle next to her, and I'd just make myself ramen or whatever we had left in the cupboard. At school, I was basically furniture. Not bullied, not popular. Just there. I'd sit in the back, do my work, go home, repeat. I had this one hoodie I wore almost every day because it had big pockets and I could just disappear into it. Teachers knew my name, but that was about it. I was the kid who turned in assignments on time and never caused problems, so nobody really looked twice. My birthday that year was on a Tuesday. I woke up, got dressed, went to school. My mom didn't say anything because she probably didn't even know what day it was. I didn't tell anyone because what was the point? At lunch, I sat alone like always, eating the free meal they gave out. And I just thought about how this was my 14th birthday. And it felt exactly like a random Wednesday in March. Then in homeroom that morning, Miss Harmon called me over to her desk. She taught English, and I had her for Third period. But homeroom was just where they took attendance and made announcements. I walked up, thinking maybe I forgot to turn something in or messed up a paper. She had this little white box on her desk, wrapped in shiny blue paper with a silver ribbon. Hey, I think this is yours, she I said, holding it out. I just stared at it. What? It's for you. Open it. My hands were shaking a little when I took it. I didn't understand what was happening. The wrapping paper made that crinkling sound when I tore it, and inside was this tiny silver necklace with a heart charm. It wasn't fancy. Probably cost like 10 bucks at the mall, but I looked at it like someone just handed me a bar of gold. I heard you mentioned last week your birthday was coming up, Miss Harmon said, smiling. Figured you should have something to Mark the day. I don't even remember telling anyone my birthday. Maybe I said it to someone in passing or wrote it on.

That was hilarious, right? Your son still won't talk to you, but at least you got a funny story out of it. My mom covered her mouth trying not to laugh, and my dad had to look away. At New Year's, when he tried to make a toast, I jumped up first. Let me tell a joke first. What do you call a guy who's been divorced three times, lost every business he started, and still gives relationship and financial advice? Uncle Tommy. Get it? Because it's funny how he thinks anyone should listen to him. Uncle Tommy finally lost it. You think you're so funny, don't you? He screamed at me while spit flew out of his mouth, making jokes about my divorces and my mistakes like you're some kind of comedian. It's not funny. It's just mean and disrespectful. I smiled at him, real calm. But, Uncle Tommy, you said if we can't laugh at ourselves, we'll never make it in life. I'm just helping you laugh at yourself. Why is it suddenly not funny when the jokes are about you? The whole room went dead silent, and Uncle Tommy's face looked like it might explode. Remember when you made my sister cry about her weight at her graduation? I kept going. Or that Super funny bit where you told Kim's kids their dad was too stupid to get a real job. Was that funny, Uncle Tommy? My mom stood up and crossed her arms. Yeah, Tommy, explain to us why your jokes are funny but his aren't. Uncle Tommy tried to say I was attacking him, but my dad said, now you know how your jokes feel to everyone else. Maybe you should think about. Uncle Tommy sat back down and didn't make any more mean jokes. But when he went for dessert, I said, that's your third piece of pie, Uncle Tommy. It's a good thing your new girlfriend doesn't care about your dad bought as long as you have money. Uncle Tommy just put his head down and pushed his plate away.

I started roasting my uncle at every family gathering until he cried on Thanksgiving. Uncle Tommy walked through the door and immediately came over to where I was practicing piano. Still wasting your parents money on those piano lessons? He said. Hey, everyone, listen to this. It sounds like someone's torturing a bunch of sick geese while they're trying to sing the national anthem. Oh, wait, that's just my nephew playing piano. Everyone laughed nervously, and I turned around on the bench. Uncle Tommy, that's really mean. I've been practicing for months. Could you please stop? He rolled his eyes at me. Don't be such a baby. It's just a joke. If you can't laugh at yourself, you'll never make it in life, kiddo. Then he walked over to my cousin Kim, who just got engaged last month. Hey, everyone, wanna start a betting pool? He was grinning. I give this marriage six months, tops. We all know how desperate Kim was to find anyone who would marry her. Kim's face went bright red, and her fiance looked like he wanted to leave right then. Uncle Tommy kept going, pointing at my sister. Speaking of desperation, here's our family teacher. You know what's funny about teachers? They get paid in crayon drawings and apple juice because that's all they're worth. He laughed at his own joke. At least the kids in your class have someone at their level to relate to, right? My sister ran out of the room. My Grandpa laughed. Kids really are too sensitive. Tommy's just joking around. My aunt nodded and added, it's just his sense of humor. You all need to learn to take a joke. By the time dinner was over, Kim had left early and my sister wouldn't come out of her room. At Christmas, I came ready with my own jokes about Uncle Tommy's life. He walked in wearing another expensive suit, and I announced to everyone, hey, look, everyone! Uncle Tommy wore his fancy suit! You know, the one he bought before his third wife took everything, including his house and his last bit of self respect. His eye twitched, but he laughed it off. Have you ever been mistaken for a celebrity's bodyguard at a Buffalo Wild Wings? Last month I stopped at Buffalo Wild Wings after my kickboxing class. I was wearing all black compression pants, a tank top, and I hadn't showered yet. My hair was in a tight bun, and I probably looked intimidating. Whatever. I just wanted boneless wings. I'm sitting at the bar, scrolling through my phone when this guy in designer sunglasses and a baseball cap walks in. He's got that trying not to be noticed vibe that actually makes you more noticeable. He sits two seats away from me, orders a beer, and keeps glancing around nervously. Then a group of college kids spots him. One girl gasps loudly and whispers to her friends there, all staring and pulling out phones. The guy tenses up. That's when one of the girls approaches me instead of him. Excuse me, can we get a photo with him? We'll be super quick. I blink. With who? She gestures toward the guy. We know you're working, but we're huge fans. Just one picture? Oh. Oh, no. She thinks I'm his bodyguard. The guy is watching this interaction with growing panic. Before I can correct her, he gives me this desperate, pleading look. For some inexplicable reason, I make a split second decision to play along. He's off duty right now, I say in my most authoritative voice. He's trying to enjoy a private meal. The girl's face falls. We understand. Sorry. To bother you. She returns to her table, and they're all whispering excitedly about how he has a bodyguard. The guy visibly relaxes. He leans over slightly. Thank you so much. I'm sorry for dragging you into this. No problem. Though I have no idea who you are. He looks genuinely relieved. Perfect. We keep it that way. Deal. We go back to our respective phones and wings. I assume that's the end of it. Then another group approaches. This time it's three guys in fraternity shirts. Yo, is that really him? One asks me. I channel every bouncer I've ever seen at a club. Guys, he's eating. Give him some space. We just get an autograph. Not tonight. They actually back off. The guy, whoever he is, mouths, thank you again. This happens four more times over the next 30 minutes. Each time, I turn people away with various professional sounding excuses. I'm fully committed to this spit now. A manager eventually approaches me. Ma'am, we appreciate you keeping things calm, but we can't have you acting as unofficial security. It's a liability issue. Totally understand, I say. The guy overhears and immediately stands up. She's with me. We'll just get our food to go. He pays both our tabs before I can protest, and we end up standing outside in the parking lot with take out bags. I'm really sorry about all that, he says, finally taking off the sunglasses. I'm Damien. I'm on a reality show about House flipping season three just dropped, and apparently I'm having a moment. I'm Riley. I teach kickboxing and know nothing about house flipping shows. He laughs. That's probably why you were so convincing. Actual bodyguards are usually more polite. We end up sitting on the tailgate of my truck, eating wings and talking. He tells me about how weird his life got after the show aired.

My sister boasted at the funeral that she was the only one dad ever trusted. I told everyone something that made the entire chapel gas. My sister Emily always acted like she was Dad's favorite. At his funeral last week, she proved it in the worst possible way. I was sitting in the front row when Emily stood up during the eulogy. The. The chapel was packed, maybe 200 people. Sounds fair until you realize my mom had nothing left over ever. So while Amy and Ada were going on trips to Disney World and getting new clothes every season, Josh and I were wearing hand me downs and staying home. The worst part wasn't even that, though. He had to share one bedroom in a four bedroom house because my stepdad said since he paid more of the mortgage, my mom's contribution only covered one room for her kids. Amy and Ada each had their own rooms and there was still a whole guest room that just sat empty. They made fun of us constantly, all three of them. Amy would come back from vacation and show us pictures while we were eating store brand cereal for Dinner, Ada would complain about how her room wasn't big enough while Josh and I were literally stepping over each other's stuff every morning. And my stepdad would just laugh like it was all some big joke. My mom's response whenever we complained was always the same, be grateful. If it wasn't for him, we'd be living in some apartment in a bad area, as if being treated like second class citizens in our own house was supposed to be a privilege. Josh and I made a promise to each other when I was about 14, we were going to get out and we were never going to need anything from anyone ever again. We both worked our butts off. He got into tech and I went into finance. By the time I was 25, I owned my own house, no mortgage. Josh did the same.

Her own mother stopped talking to her. I came home and found her crying on the floor, surrounded by bills. Why didn't you warn me about any of this? You just watched me destroy my life. I didn't mean only compliments. She stopped because she clearly couldn't explain what she actually wanted. I pulled up my phone and read text with dates. Can we go back to normal, please? Something else had. I grabbed a tape measure, walked outside and measured. 3 feet. 3 full feet were gone. I stood there, tape measure in hand, staring at my own driveway like an idiot. Had I made a mistake? Was there some kind of property shift I didn't know about? Had I signed something and forgotten? No, that wasn't possible. I needed proof. And then I waited. A week passed. Nothing happened. I started to wonder if I'd been wrong. Maybe I really was just bad at parking. Then one night, I checked the footage, and I saw something that made my blood boil. At 2:00am, my neighbor walked into my driveway. He Looked around, making sure no one was watching. Then a truck pulled. A crew of guys got out, and right there in the dead of night, they started working on his driveway. But they weren't fixing it. They were expanding it onto mine. I watched in stunned silence as they ripped up the old boundary line, poured new asphalt three feet over onto my property, and painted fresh white lines like it had always been that way. They even sprayed a new border on my driveway like they owned it. I couldn't believe what I was seeing. Who does that? Who? Just take

What stupid rule did your parents make that backfired spectacularly? My mom had a complete meltdown because I told her the new highlights looked orange. She screamed that I always criticized her, that I never appreciated anything. We fought for two hours straight. She was recently divorced after 20 years and suddenly dating again, and every honest comment became a personal attack for her. So she made a rule. I had to send her three compliments every day by text, or I'd lose my car for a week. I need to know you actually see the good in me. She said, fine, whatever. I agreed immediately because no car meant no life, and started sending compliments every morning. But I also stopped giving her any other feedback about anything. She had no idea what she just done. The very first week, her yoga friend offered kitchen microblading. I watched my mom pack up to go. The friends photos online showed no gloves, no sterile equipment, just a card table with a towel. I said nothing. My mom came home with eyebrows that got infected three days later and scarred permanently. The compliment I had to give her was, your determination to try new things is really inspiring, mom. The second week, she started dating someone who forgot his wallet three dates in a row. He even asked for $200 for car repairs, and she wrote the check. Then he moved in a week later, just temporarily. I actually saw him. On dating apps. While she worked, he ate our food, used our accounts, and made messes everywhere. So when she asked if I liked him, I just said, you're so generous and trusting, mom. Week 3, the same guy had a friend with a crypto investment opportunity. My mom didn't understand, but he showed her charts, and she asked my opinion. I just said, do whatever makes you happy. She invested $5,000, and all the money vanished in four days. Total scam. That compliment that morning was, you're always willing to believe in people, mom. The next month, it got so much worse. My dad was dating a new woman, and the wedding invitation finally arrived. My mom went full unhinged mode.

My driveway kept getting smaller. Every month it looked like the line was moving. I brought out my old house plans and measured. Three feet were missing. I've lived in my New Jersey house for over 20 years. Nothing fancy, but it's mine. When I bought it, I made sure everything was documented properly. Property lines, ease it's boundaries, all the legal stuff. I didn't want problems down the road. My driveway was clearly mine, my neighbor's fence was his, and the space between was a clear boundary. Simple, no problems. Till one day I pulled into my driveway and something felt wrong. At first I thought maybe I was imagining things. My driveway felt narrower. I wasn't sure why, but I had to park closer to my garage door than usual. It wasn't a big deal. Maybe I just parked weird. That day. I let it go. Then it happened again and again. A few months passed and every time I came home it felt worse. I started second guessing myself. Was I losing my mind? Had my driveway always been this tight? I asked my wife if she noticed anything. She looked at me like I was crazy. You're just bad at parking, she said. Maybe she was right. I let it go. Until one morning when I was pulling out and my tire hit something. A hard edge that was completely new. I got out and looked. There was a fresh strip pavement along the edge of my Driveway blending into mine like it had always been there. But it hadn't. I squatted down, running my hand over it. The asphalt was smoother than the rest of my driveway. It was fresh. I glanced over at my neighbor's driveway. That looked new, too. It clicked. I didn't know how, I didn't know when, but my neighbor had stolen part of my driveway. I didn't say anything yet. I wanted proof first. I went inside, dug through my old paper.

My wife divorced me by email while I was deployed overseas. She emptied our joint account and moved her new boyfriend into our house. I responded calmly, understood. When she realized what I had done, it was already too late. The email came while I was in Kandahar. Subject? Let's be adults about this. Three sentences. She'd filed the paperwork, emptied our joint account, moved Jeremy into our house. 13 years of marriage ended in a PDF. I read it twice, closed my laptop, said nothing to anyone. That night. I replied, understood. Truth is, I wasn't surprised. 6 months before deployment, things had changed. New clothes, late nights, gym membership she never used. I didn't confront her. That's not who I am. But I made quiet moves. Secured documents in a storage unit. House deed with only my name thanks to the VA loan. Opened a separate account. Diverted part of my pay. Not enough she'd notice, but enough. I wouldn't start from zero. What she didn't know was that I'd prepare. And I never start fights. But I finish them. Two weeks later, $88,500 withdrawn. Everything gone. Balance twenty two dollars and sixty seven cents. I called the bank. Becky had been moving money for weeks. Big transfers started the day after I deployed. I logged into our home security system. Something Becky forgot I could access. Strange truck in my driveway. A man using my coffee mug, wearing my Seahawks sweatshirt. Walking my dog. And Becky laughing. In the kitchen I'd renovated, something cold settled in my chest. I made a list. Called James. Army buddy turned lawyer. Check VA loan terms, review refinance documents. This wasn't about emotion. This was strategy. At 0 500, I emailed James. Need legal help? Urgent. Two months later, I was stateside. Didn't tell Becky. Checked into a motel under a different name. James met me with a folder. Found something interesting. A refinance application with my signature. Except it wasn't mine. Middle initial, wrong stroke pattern off. Becky forged it three months ago. Used the equity to pull $165,000. Your signature is required for VA loans. So she faked it. And she listed her boyfriend as co applicant. He's got two DUIs and a fraud charge. I showed the bank my military ID, my real signature, the forged documents. His face went pale. I've already filed a police report.

At my housewarming, my sister announced, your 960,000 dollar house is perfect for my kids. Then mom said, pack your bags. I smiled, took out my phone, and showed them the document that changed everything. The marble countertops and hardwood floors in my new home represent every all nighter I pulled building my tech company. But watching my sister Cassandra strut in with our mother, Eleanor, something in their expressions makes my skin crawl. I've seen that look before. When I was 18. The night that changed everything. Growing up in Boston, Cassandra was always the golden child. When she married into money at 22, mom spent $50,000 on her wedding. I was 19, working two jobs through community college. Each of Cassandra's three children, she grew more entitled to family support. Despite marrying rich, they lived beyond their means. When they hit financial trouble, mom bailed them out at my expense. Sister has three children to feed, mom would say. What do you need extra money for? Meanwhile, I worked myself to exhaustion. Barista in the mornings, tutor in the afternoons, data entry on weekends. On my 18th birthday, I found them at the kitchen table with my college paperwork. I need your college fund, mom stated. Cassandra needs a bigger house. You have scholarships already. My college fund? The money dad set aside before the divorce. That's my money for education, I said. Cassandra rolled her eyes. Don't be selfish. We're talking about a home for your niece. And nephews take out loans like everyone else. Years of being second best finally broke something inside me. No. Mom's expression hardened. If that's your attitude, pack your bags. Your 18 now. I packed that night, slept in my car for two weeks. In February in Boston, my computer science professor noticed me dozing in the library. She gave me her guest room and helped me secure scholarships. I built a financial app with my best friend. Five years later, we sold it. I became a millionaire. At 30 now. At my housewarming, Cassandra addresses my 30 guests. This house is perfect for my family, she announces. With Eric's job situation and the kids needing good schools. Hazel, single, no kids. This is wasted on one person when we have three growing children. Mom nods. Pack your bags and find a condo downtown. It's the least you could do for family. The room falls silent. I connect.

My phone to the TV. A legal document fills the screen. This is a restraining order I filed 14 years ago after you kicked me out at 18. We never kicked you out, mom protests. I slept in my car for two weeks in February in Boston. I swiped to the next screen. After I left, someone opened three credit cards and a personal loan in my name. Told full debt, $45,000. Mom goes white. Cassandra stares at her wine. The cards were used at stores Cassandra frequented. The loan deposited into an account that transferred the exact amount to Eric's checking. Eric turns to his wife. You told me that was a gift from your mother. I zoom in on the loan signature. Someone forged my name but spelled my middle name wrong. Why weren't we arrested? Cassandra asks. Cause I was 18 and terrified. I paid off all $45,000 myself over three years while working three jobs through college. Every cent plus interest. I pull up payment records. Cassandra posted vacation photos. I was eating cheap meals and pulling all nighters to pay off debt I never incurred. Eric looks ill. I swipe again. I discovered six failed business ventures Cassandra invested in without your knowledge, Eric, using joint funds. Total losses exceeded $200,000. Those were personal loans, Cassandra blurted. You came here to claim my home, assuming I'd sacrifice myself again for Cassandra's wants. I say calmly, that will never happen. Where is your compassion? Mom demands Where was yours when I was sleeping in my car when you stole my identity before I'd even started college? Mom grabs her purse. Cassandra, we're leaving. My business partner Stephanie speaks up. This is a Celebration of Hazel's home, not a venue for attempted property theft. Eric stays. Days later, he files for divorce after discovering more hidden debts. I established education funds for my niece and nephews, accounts that can only be used for school, protecting them from history repeating itself. The journey from sleeping in my car at 18 to owning this home at 32 wasn't just about financial success. It was about reclaiming my worth and refusing to be a doormat ever again.

Bag. Who the hell are you? I jumped up. I'm house sitting for Jen. The woman grabbed her phone, hands shaking. We don't know any Jen. You broke into our house? I started panicking. No, no. She gave me the address. I have texts. The man yelled at me to stay where I was and called 9 1 1. I was crying at this point, trying to pull up Jen's messages on my phone to prove I wasn't some crazy burglar. The cops showed up in, like, five minutes. Two officers, one older guy and a younger woman. They asked for my ID and started going through my phone. I showed them everything. Jen's texts, the address, the pictures of the dog. The older cop squinted at the screen. This says 54B Oakridge Court. You're on Oakridge Lane. My stomach dropped. Court Lane. I'd gone to the wrong street. I looked at the couple. I'm so sorry. I swear I thought this was the right house. The woman was crying now, too. You've been here all weekend? You slept here? You fed our dog there? Dog? Not Daisy, their dog. Turns out they've been out of town visiting their daughter. They came home early because their flight got moved up. And I've been living in their house, eating their food, walking their dog, posting pictures online like some psycho. The younger cop asked if anything was missing. The couple checked and said no, but the man kept saying she was In our home, she slept in our bed even though I didn't. I slept in the guest room, but he wasn't listening because I'd use their key, eaten their food, stayed multiple nights, and posted online from inside their house. They said it counted as trespassing and unlawful occupancy. Officer told me I was being arrested. I started sobbing, still in my pajamas. They cuffed me right there in the living room. At the station, I called Jen, freaking out. She didn't answer at first because she was still at the wedding. When she finally called back, she was confused as hell. She confirmed the address was Oakridge Court, not Lane, and said her neighbor had been watching Daisy the whole time. She had to drive three hours to come explain everything in person. Even then, I still got charged. I had to go to court twice. Couple didn't press charges for theft, but I got fined for trespassing. Almost $800. Jen felt awful and gave me the hundred bucks anyway, but it didn't even cover a quarter of what I owed. I had to pick up extra shifts for two months just to pay it off. My mugshot's still online if you search my name.

I opened the back door and this golden retriever came running up, tail wagging like crazy. I assumed it was Daisy. The dog was super friendly, jumping all over me, licking my hands. Monday afternoon I was on the couch in my pajamas watching some true crime show when I heard the front door unlock. I froze. This older couple, probably in their 60s, walked in carrying suitcases. They saw me and literally screamed. The man dropped his.
