His voice carried across the rooftop as he described closing some massive deal. Gesturing with his drink, Caitlin rolled her eyes saying something about finance bros always being the loudest people at any party. Monday morning would bring three final interviews for the senior developer position at my company, Next Forge Solutions, and I've been reviewing resumes all week. The tall guy from the bar started moving through the crowd, his entourage following like Pilot Fish and I shifted position to avoid their path. But rooftop parties have limited space and he was heading straight toward us. His group surrounded us before I could suggest moving. Their conversation drowning out the ambient music. Caitlin tried to continue talking but gave up when one of his friends literally stepped between. I backed up against the railing to give them space, but the tall guy turned suddenly with his drink held loosely and the entire contents of his whiskey sour splashed across my chest. The cold liquid soaked through my henley immediately, ice cubes bouncing off my stomach. For a moment, everyone in the immediate vicinity went quiet. I look down at my ruined shirt then back up at him. He stared at me like I'd materialized out of nowhere. His face showing annoyance rather than apology. I waited for the automatic sorry that should follow accidentally dumping a drink on someone. Instead, he looked me up and down with obvious disdain, taking in my wet discount clothing. His friends were watching now sensing entertainment and he played to the audience. He said in a voice loud enough for half the rooftop to hear that maybe I should buy better clothes if I wanted to hang out at places like this. The word peasant came out of his mouth with such casual cruelty, I actually wondered if I'd misheard him. Caitlin's face went from shocked to furious in seconds, but I put a hand on her arm before she could tear into him. The tall guys friends started laughing, one of them making a comment about the dress code. Being pretty relaxed these days, pulled a money clip from his pocket, peeled off a twenty dollar Bill and tried to hand it to me while suggesting I use it to upgrade my wardrobe. The humiliation was clearly intentional, designed to establish hierarchy in front of his audience. I didn't take the money, just stood there dripping whiskey. He let the Bill flutter to the ground between us, said something about some people not knowing how to accept help and turned back to his friends like I'd ceased to. They moved away, still laughing. Caitlin immediately started pulling napkins from her purse, asking if I was okay. I wiped off what I could, but the shirt was ruined and the smell of whiskey clung to me.

My husband said his mom felt left out on Facebook, so I included her in everything. My husband completely lost his mind over a Facebook comment his mother made on our anniversary post. We were having breakfast when he pulled up his phone and showed me the screen like he just discovered evidence of a crime. My mom feels excluded from our marriage and I think we need to fix this. Immediately, I stared at the comment, which literally just said, wish I could have joined you two lovebirds with a smiley face emoji under a photo of our anniversary dinner at an expensive steakhouse. She's being passive aggressive about feeling left out and I won't stand for it. Family should always be included. I looked at this man who once told his mother she couldn't stay over because we needed space. She lives 40 minutes away and we see her every Sunday for dinner already. That's exactly the problem. We're not making enough effort to include her in our daily lives and she's obviously crying for help through social media. The comment had three likes and his mom had posted 12 recipes and a cat video since writing it. So what exactly are you proposing here, I asked. He needs to be included in everything we do as a couple from now on to repair this relationship. Family doesn't have boundaries and my mother deserves better from us. I paused, then smiled sweetly and said, you're absolutely right, honey. The very next morning, I called his mother while he was in the shower. I need you at my gynecologist appointment in an hour because your son says you were excluded from our marriage. Dead silence on the other end before she finally spoke. He saw your anniversary comment and decided you need to be included in everything now. I explained that was just a nice comment because the restaurant looked fancy in the picture. She protested, well, you're coming to my pap smear now because family has no boundaries. She showed up confused but brought coffee. My husband's face when he came home to find us discussing my cervical health over wine was priceless. Two days later, I brought her to our couple's therapy session where she sat between us taking notes. The therapist kept asking why my mother in law was present. My husband insisted because of her Facebook comment, I explained, while his mother nervously suggested we should try date nights and therapy without her. But you were so excluded, remember, I reminded her that evening I called her while my husband and I were getting intimate. Your son wants you included, so you're on.

My dad saved my life by not answering his phone. It was December, finals week at State University, and I was practically living in the library. Third floor computer lab section, surrounded by towers of textbooks and empty energy drink cans. The place was packed with stressed students cramming for exams. I'd been there since six PM, grinding through calculus problems. My study group had abandoned me around 8, but I was determined to master these integration problems before for tomorrow's exam. Around nine PM, I was deep into my calculus review when everything went black. Complete darkness. Not just the lights. Everything. Computers, emergency exit signs. Even the hum of the ventilation system stopped. At first, people laughed nervously and pulled out their phones for flashlights. Someone joked about not having to take finals if the power stayed out. The mood was almost festive. But that didn't last long. Maybe 10 minutes passed before we heard shouting from the main floor. A man's voice shouting that everyone needed to evacuate immediately. Something about a gas leak. His voice carried that urgent authority that makes you move without thinking. Students started rushing toward the stairwells. In the darkness. It was chaos. People bumping into tables, books crashing to the floor, nervous laughter turning into real panic. I got caught in the crowd, pushed along with everyone else. The stairwell was packed, bodies pressed together, people using phone flashlights that created more shadows than light. But something felt wrong. The guy's Voice had an edge to it that didn't sound like campus security. And why would a gas leak require cutting all power to the building? When we reached the stairwell, the crowd bottlenecked. People were shoving. Someone dropped their laptop in the confusion. I got separated. Instead of fighting through, I ducked back into the computer lab. The room was eerily quiet now. All those stressed students had vanished, leaving behind their abandoned belongings. That's when I heard them. Multiple voices. Definitely not students. They were talking in hushed tones, but their words carried in the empty building. They were moving systematically through each floor, checking rooms, opening doors. I crept behind a row of desktop computers and server towers, trying to make myself invisible. My heart was pounding so loud, I was sure they'd hear it. My phone started buzzing. Dad calling. Then again. Then again. I wanted desperately to answer, to tell him I was okay, to ask him what to do. But something in my gut told me to stay silent. The voices got closer. I could hear footsteps in the hallway, doors opening and closing. They were being thorough, checking every room methodically. These weren't security guards doing a safety sweep.

My father refused to walk me down the aisle because my sister, who hates me, organized a party on the same day. Then he called me, desperate when he found out I had already found someone better to accompany me. My sister Kira was always the golden child. I was the accident that came 11 months later. My mother kept my hospital bracelet in a drawer labeled oops until I could read it myself. At age six, favoritism was constant. Kira got new clothes every season, while I wore her hand me downs. Christmas, when I turned 8, I watched her unwrap the American Girl doll I begged Santa for. My gift was a dollar store knock off with the $1 99 cent sticker still on it. When I started crying, my father said, Selena, you're too old for tears. Kira is more sensitive than you. That was the moment I Learned I had to hide my emotions to avoid disappointing them further. Middle school was worse. My eighth grade graduation, I won three academic awards while Kira sat in the audience getting seas. During the car ride home, instead of celebrating my achievements, my parents spent the entire time discussing how Kira must feel seeing me on stage so, so much. My mother said, Selena, maybe next time don't look so excited when they call your name. Think about your sister's feelings. In high school, I pulled straight A's while Kira barely passed. When report cards came home, they Pin hers to the fridge and put mine in a drawer. The day I got accepted to Northwestern with a full scholarship, I found my parents comforting Kira, who just been fired from her clothing store job for showing up late. My mother looked at my acceptance letter and said, Selena, this really isn't the time. Can't you see your sister is upset? They spent an hour consoling her for losing a minimum wage job while completely ignoring my full scholarship that would save them $200,000. That night, my aunt Sandra told me something that changed everything. Selena, you were never an accident. Your parents did fertility treatments to give Kira a sibling, but when you turned out smarter than her, they didn't know how to handle it. Everything clicked into place. Constant comparisons, the downplaying of my achievements, the way they seemed annoyed when I succeeded. College became my escape. I met Matt there, someone who valued my intelligence instead of feeling threatened by it.
NA

I kicked out my brother who our parents have previously disowned because he told my now ex fiance that I cheated nine years ago. So my brother Connor is 19. I'm 26. My ex fiance hunter is 28. Connor got kicked out by our parents when he was 16 because they went through his phone and found out he was gay. Like they literally just told him to leave and never come back. It was brutal. So I took him in because what else was I supposed to do? He's my little brother. Last weekend was Connor's birthday and he had a bunch of his friends over. They were all drinking and playing games, just being loud college aged kids. Hunter and I were about to leave and give them the place when Connor asked if we wanted to join. I said no at first because I'm way too old for drinking games. But Connor kept insisting and hunter thought it'd be fun to relive our college days for tonight. We all got pretty drunk, like really drunk. Connor suggested we play Never Have I Ever and everyone was into it. We're going around saying dumb stuff like never have I ever skinny dipped or whatever. Then someone says never have I ever cheated before. Here's the thing, hunter absolutely hates cheaters. His ex fiance cheated on him years ago and it completely destroyed him. He's told me multiple times that cheating is the one thing he can never forgive. And when I was 17, I did something really stupid. I cheated on my boyfriend of five months. It was a horrible mistake. He found out, dumped me, and I felt like garbage. That was almost 10 years ago. I Learned my lesson hard and I've never done anything like that since. I'm not that person anymore. So when the cheating question came up, I didn't drink. I figured it was so long ago and it was just some high school boyfriend that it didn't really count. But Connor was drunk and apparently his filter was completely gone because he goes, hey, sis, what the hell? You cheated on Jason back in high school? Got a drink. To that, the room went quiet. Hunter just stopped moving. He looked at me, then at Connor, then back at me. Then he got up and walked straight out of the room without saying a word. I followed him immediately and tried to explain that it was a stupid teenage mistake from almost a decade ago, that I was a completely different person now, that it had nothing to do with us. He wouldn't even look at me. He just said he couldn't be with someone who had cheated before, that it didn't matter when it happened, and that we were done. Then he left. I stood there in complete shock. Hunter was everything to me. We've been together for three years. We were supposed to get married in six months. I had The dress. We had the venue booked and it was just gone in like 5 minutes because of something I did when I was a stupid kid. Connor came out and tried to apologize. He was crying and saying he didn't think that he was just drunk and being dumb, that he didn't mean to ruin anything. But I couldn't even look at him. I just went to my room and locked the door. I heard him knocking and apologizing through the door for like an hour, but I ignored him. Next morning, I printed out an eviction notice and handed it to him. He looked at it and started begging me not to kick him out. He said he was so sorry that it was an accident, that he'd do anything to fix it. But I told him he needed to leave. He ruined my entire life in one drunk sentence. After everything I did for him, I took him in when our parents abandoned him. I paid for his food.

My barber stopped cutting and asked, why do you have the same tattoo as the missing person poster outside? I froze in the chair, Scissors still hovering over my head. What missing person poster, I asked. But Tony was already walking to the window. He pointed at a flyer taped to the glass outside his shop. That one missing guy named Jake Morrison. Same eagle tattoo on the left shoulder blade, same scar through the wing from what I can see. My stomach dropped because my name was Jake Morrison and I definitely had that exact tattoo. Tony, that's probably just a coincidence. Lots of people have eagle tattoos. But Tony was shaking his head, studying my reflection in the mirror. Jake, I've been cutting your hair for two years. Never seen your full name anywhere until today. And this poster says, Jake Morrison went missing three months ago. He showed me his appointment book, but you've been coming here every month like clockwork. I twisted around to look at the poster through the window. The photo was grainy and taken from a distance, but it definitely looked like me. Same build, same hair color, same general features. This has to be some mistake, I said, but my voice sounded shaky even to me. Maybe there's another Jake Morrison with a similar tattoo. Tony pulled the poster off his window and brought it inside. Says, here, he disappeared from Portland, Oregon on March 15th. His family is offering a ten thousand Dollar reward. He looked at me carefully. Jake, where were you living before you moved here? I tried to remember, but my memories before arriving in this town were surprisingly fuzzy. I came from the East Coast, said, but even as I said it, I wasn't sure if that was true. Been traveling around for work. Tony raised an eyebrow. What kind of work? I opened my mouth to answer and realized I couldn't remember what I told him. Before construction, I said finally, but it felt like a guess. Tony set down his Scissors completely. Jake, this is serious. If this is you on this poster, your family thinks you're dead or kidnapped. There are people looking for you. He pulled out his phone. Maybe we should call the number and clear this up. My heart started racing and I didn't know why wait, I said, grabbing his wrist. Let me think about this first. If I call that number and it's not me, I'll be wasting everyone's time. And if it is me, I trailed off because I couldn't finish that thought. If it was me, then I had no memory of having a family or disappearing from anywhere. Tony sat down in the chair next to me. Jake, when you first came to my shop, you paid cash, said you were new in town, starting fresh, but you never talked about where you came from or why you moved here. That seemed normal at the time, but Now he gestured at the poster. Now it seems like maybe you were running from something. Stared at my reflection, trying to remember my life before this town. I had an apartment here, a job at the hardware store, a routine. But when I tried to think further back, everything got blurry. I think I might have been in an accident, I said slowly. Hit my head or something. My memory of the past few years is pretty foggy. That would explain a lot, Tony said gently. Head injuries can cause amnesia. Maybe you disappeared from Port.

I enforced basic boundaries on my daughter's sleepover. I have two kids. My daughter Anya is 17 and my stepson Noah is 14. Noah's mom died a few years back and he's been living with me full time since. He's not like some weird loner kid or anything, but he really doesn't like when people mess with his stuff or invade his space. When he gets really overwhelmed, he just kind of shuts down completely and won't talk to anyone for a while. Anya's the total opposite. She's super outgoing, always has friends over, constantly on her phone with someone. Last Thursday, she asked if she could have four friends sleep over on Saturday night. I said, yeah, sure. But I gave her two rules. First, her friends needed to stay out of Noah's room completely. They're kind of loud, and in the past they've crowded him and made him uncomfortable. Second, keep the noise down after 11 so the rest of us could actually sleep. That's it. Two basic rules that any normal person should be able to follow. Saturday comes around and her friends show up around six. They're making dinner, blasting music, laughing super loud in the kitchen. Totally fine. I was downstairs watching TV and honestly wasn't paying much attention. I figured they were seventeen years old, I didn't need to babysit them every five minutes. Around ten I decided to go upstairs and just do a quick check to make sure everything was cool before I went to bed. I walk past Anya's room, and it's empty. We weird. I hear voices coming from down the hall, and my stomach just drops because I immediately know where they are. I open Noah's door, and all five of them are in there. Two of the girls are literally sitting on his bed like they own the place. One of them has his sketchbook open and is flipping through it while the others are giggling. Another girl is going through the stuff on his desk, picking up his headphones and looking at his drawings pinned to the wall. They're all laughing in this way that made my skin crawl, like they thought the whole thing was hilarious. Noah was sitting on the floor in the corner near his closet. He wasn't saying anything. He wasn't moving, but I could see tears in his eyes and his hands were shaking a little. I said his name twice, and he didn't even look at me. That's when I knew he'd completely shut down. I told all the girls to get out of the room right now. Anya started to say something, but I cut her off and told her I was calling all of their parents immediately. She looked at me like I just told her I was burning her phone. One of her friends tried to laugh it off and said they were just talking to him, but I didn't care. I pointed at the door and told Them to go downstairs and wait in the living room. Anya followed me out into the hallway and started saying I was being ridiculous and embarrassing her in front of her friends. I told her I gave her two rules, and she couldn't even follow one of them. She said they were just trying to include Noah and be nice. I asked her if he looked included to her. She didn't have an answer for that. I went back into Noah's room and sat on the floor next to him. I didn't try to make him talk or anything. I just told him I was sorry and that they were leaving. After about 15 minutes, he finally said he wanted to be alone for a while. I told him that was fine and left him there with his door closed. I went downstairs and called every single parent. I explained what happened and said they needed to come pick up their kids. Anya stood there the whole time.

What made you realize you were the villain in someone's story? When I was 19, I thought I was the cool older cousin. Every family gathering I'd mess with my 12 year old cousin Jacob. I'd call him Bambi because he was clumsy, hide his Nintendo DS and once convinced him wasabi was guacamole. Everyone laughed when he ran to the kitchen crying and chugging milk. Even his parents chuckled and said boys will be boys. I filmed half of it on my phone. Jacob trying not to cry when I'd flick his ears, him stumbling when I'd stick my foot out, me zooming in on his red face after pranks. I thought I was making hilarious family memories. Jacob used to follow me around like a puppy before I started messing with him. He'd ask about high school, wanted to play video games together, even copied how I styled my hair. I thought the teasing was just normal cousin stuff. My friends did worse to their little brothers. But then Jacob stopped coming to family stuff. His mom would say he had too much homework or wasn't feeling good or had plans with friends. I didn't really care. Less annoying little kid energy at barbecues. Years went by. I graduated college, moved to Portland, got a decent job, barely thought about family back home except for the occasional Facebook scroll. Then my aunt died in a car accident. I flew back for the funeral, hadn't seen most of my Family in like three years after the service, we all went to my uncle's house for food and stories. I was grabbing a sandwich when this tall guy in a gray hoodie walked in.

My girlfriend told me I was just a placeholder until she finished having fun. I started living like she didn't exist and watched her lose her mind. When she came back, Brooke and I had been together for two and a/2 years. She was the outgoing party girl. I was the chill plumber who kept things. First year was great. She got me out of my comfort zone. I introduced her to my dad, Jim. We seemed to fit. Year 2, everything shifted. She started disappearing on weekend trips with her friend, Rebecca, a festival influencer who constantly preached about how Brooke was too young to be tied down. The breaking point came over dinner when I asked if she'd be my date to my friend's wedding in October. She literally laughed. October? That's five months away. Who knows where we'll be then? What do you mean where we'll be? She took a sip of her wine and looked at me like I was being dense. Ryan, let's be real. This is fun, but I'm not ready to settle down yet. I wanna travel, meet new people. So what am I to you? Exactly. She actually thought about it, taking another sip like she was contemplating world peace. You're comfortable, safe. You're like a security blanket. You're the kind of guy I'll come back to when I'm ready for all that serious stuff. But right now, you're just a phase while I figure out what I really want. Just the phase Those words hit me like a physical blow. When I'm like 28 or 29, I'll be ready for the settling down thing. And you assume I'll just wait around. She shrugged. Why wouldn't you? I just need to get this party phase out of my system first. You'll still be here doing your plumber thing, being stable. I was literally a bookmark in her life story. Good to know where I stand. I said that night I called my dad and told him everything. His response was simple. She just told you exactly who she is. Believe her now. Act accordingly. If I was just a placeholder, I'd start acting like it. I stopped investing completely. No more buying groceries for her place. No more meeting her party friends while she was at festivals, posting Instagram stories. I quietly rebuilt my life, joined a hiking group, started teaching kids loading at the community center. And then I did the big thing, bought a house. I've been saving for years, always telling myself I was waiting for us. Well, if there was no us, why was I waiting? Found this incredible 1954 fixer upper, 3 bedroom, original hardwood, mid century fireplace. Dad came to look at it, foundation, solid. You'd be stupid not to buy it. Put in an offer without telling Brooke. She was at Coachella posting stories, got the acceptance text while she sent me videos captioned miss you, babe. That's when I met Sophie through the hiking group. Personal trainer, 23, dry sense of humor. Whoever decided raisins belong in trail mix clearly hates joy. She said on our first hike. We started hiking together. She helped me pick tile for the renovation. Turns out her dad's a contractor and she knows more about grout than most people at the gym. For seven months, I kept Brooke completely separate from my new life, changed all my privacy settings, avoided posting anything revealing. But secrets don't last. At a family barbecue, my cousin mentioned seeing me at the park with someone, Brooke, immediately.

Happened after you got pregnant? As a teenager, when I broke down and told my dad that I was pregnant, he didn't care that it was because a man twice my age forced himself on me. All he saw was disgrace to the family. He threw me out in the snow in the middle of the night. I spent the night in the park bathroom trying not to freeze to death while touching my stomach and thinking about this baby I never wanted. Miss Nyla found me the next morning sleeping in the school bathroom because I couldn't in the park with those men who kept circling back. She was my English teacher who always said I could write my way out of this town if I just kept believing in myself. She took one look at my garbage bags and I completely broke down. I sobbed so hard I couldn't breathe. You're coming home with me, she said. And I collapsed against her because nobody had hugged me since that night with that man and I needed someone to tell me I wasn't disgusting. She cancelled her classes and drove me to her house. I cried the whole way because kindness felt so foreign. Miss Nyla lived alone in a house full of books and cats that wouldn't leave my stomach alone, like they could sense the life inside. She made me a bedroom in her office and came to every doctor's appointment where nurses assumed she was my Mother, and we never corrected them. At night, she'd hold my hair during morning sickness and tell me about her wife, Marina, who died three years years ago. They tried for kids for a decade but ran out of time. Maybe you're both my second chance, she whispered, while I threw up again and I sobbed because this stranger was being the mother mine refused to be. We fell into a routine where she watched me do online school while I helped grade papers. Slowly, my belly grew.

Girls have read it. What's the creepiest thing a man has said to you in public? One, when you're 18, I'm going to take you to Europe, said my grade 8 teacher. Two, this old man, probably 60 something, told me I looked exactly like his favourite pornstar. 3. A homeless guy once told me he wanted to throw me in a bathtub full of jello and make love to me. 4. You don't get a view like that every day. I was 10 and bending down to get something off a lower shelf at the grocery store. I was wearing a new lower cut shirt but forgot to wear my training bra that day. The guy was mid 40s, probably his wife was with him. She looked like she was about to cry. I never wore that shirt again. 5. Told me to smile more because it makes him and his little buddy happy. Six, you don't look 13. I want your number here. 9, 1 1 7. While I was cutting a man's hair at beauty school, he told me to keep talking because it excites him a lot and proceeded to show me his mini me. 8, I was 11. In a street market in Italy, a vendor came up to me and started trying to convince me to marry his son. My dad ran up and was like, dude, she's 11. The guy said, my son's only 26. It's perfect. 9. You have all your teeth. I like that. I was waiting for the bus.

I got a call from my brother at 11 p m. On a Tuesday saying, Mom's in the hospital. You need to come quick. It's serious. I dropped everything, drove four hours through the night, panicking the whole time, and burst into the hospital waiting room. Everyone was just sitting there calmly eating subway sandwiches. Turns out it was a family intervention they planned because I work too much and never visit anymore. My hands were still shaking from the drive. I'd run two red lights. My phone had 17 missed calls from relatives I hadn't spoken to in months. And now my brother Kevin was standing there holding a Turkey sub like nothing happened. Sit down. My mom said. She wasn't even in a hospital gown, was wearing her church sweater. Are you kidding me right now? My Aunt Linda jumped in. We're worried about you, honey. You never come home anymore. You missed Thanksgiving. You missed Kevin's engagement party. I missed those things because I was building something. I had just gotten promoted to district manager. I was finally making real money after years of living off ramen and hope. But none of them asked about that. You lied about mom dying, I said slowly. Kevin shrugged. You wouldn't have come otherwise. That part was true. But not because I didn't care. Because every time I visited, it turned into this. Me getting lectured about priorities while they lived off their spouses income or dad's old business money. My mom started crying. The fake kind. I just want my son back. The old you actually cared about family. The old me worked at a grocery store and lived in their basement. The old me had time because I had nothing. I sat down. Not because I wanted to, but because my legs felt weird. What do you want from me? They had a whole list. Weekly dinners, help with Kevin's wedding planning. Showing up to Mom's book club just to be present. My dad, who hadn't said a word yet, finally spoke. You think you're too good for us now? I wasn't about to cry in front of them, so I left. I walked out of that hospital, got in my car and drove home in silence. Three months went by. No calls, no texts. I sent mom flowers on her birthday. She didn't respond. Then Kevin called. Hey, man, I need a favor. Wedding venue fell through. Can you help cover part of it? Like eight grand? $8,000? The same brother who faked a medical emergency wanted eight grand? Your family said, this is what we do. I thought about it for maybe two seconds. No, he lost it. Started yelling about how selfish I was, how I changed, how money made me cold. I hung up. A week later, my mom left a voicemail.

My wife mocked love really is blind. I married you. In front of her friends. So I opened her eyes to single life. My wife invited her college friends over for wine night. I was playing the good husband, refilling drinks and bringing out the expensive cheese board. The conversation was typical gossip until I heard her voice get louder with that tone she used for killer punch lines. You know what they say, girls, love really is blind. She gestured toward me with her wine glass as all four women turned to stare. I mean, I actually married. That proves the saying, right, doesn't it? Dead silence. Not the kind where people think of comebacks. Kind where everyone realizes they've witnessed something they shouldn't have. I stood there holding wine, watching four faces caught between nervous laughter and secondhand embarrassment. I didn't explode or storm out. I finished pouring wine, set it down and calmly walked upstairs. Behind me, I heard forced conversation starting again. 20 minutes later, she knocked on our bedroom door. Are you seriously going to be dramatic about this? It was just a joke. Did the they look like they were laughing, I asked quietly. She rolled her eyes. You're being way too sensitive. It's not like I said anything that wasn't true. There it was. Not only had she humiliated me publicly, but she was doubling down that my feelings about being treated like garbage were invalid because she just decided I was overreacting. As I lay there that night, one thought kept running through my head. She'd shown me exactly how much respect she had for me. I woke up with absolute clarity and started documenting everything, not just last night but years of incidents. I dismissed time. She introduced me to coworkers as not much to look at, but he pays the bills. Saturday morning while she was at yoga, her phone buzzed on the counter. The notification showed a group chat called Wine Night Girls with the message preview containing my name. Her passcode was our wedding anniversary. The messages were all there. She'd immediately shared what she'd said about me with laughing emojis, calling her friends. Reactions priceless. One friend asked if she was serious. Her response, dead serious. I mean, look at him, but he's stable and worships the ground I walk on. So whatever. Months of conversations where I was the running joke, comments about my appearance, screenshots of my texts shared for mockery, pictures of gifts I'd given her with captions about how sweet but clueless I was. I took screenshots and called a divorce attorney Monday. The attorney reviewed the evidence. This shows deliberate emotional abuse. These messages prove she views the marriage as transact.

I didn't wake up my girlfriend for her exam after I overheard her calling me a little bitch. So I've been with my girlfriend for about two years now. Things were pretty good, or at least I thought they were. She's always been kind of a heavy sleeper, like not just normal heavy sleeper, but the kind where her phone alarm can go off for 20 minutes straight and she'll just roll over and turn it off in her sleep without even knowing. I started waking her up for stuff early on because she missed a dentist appointment once and was super stressed about. It became our thing. I guess I didn't really mind at first, like, yeah, sometimes I'd rather sleep in, but that's what you do in a relationship, right? You help each other out. She had summer classes online this year, which meant exams at home. The night before her big exam, I was in the kitchen grabbing water around midnight when I heard her on the phone with her friends in the living room. She didn't know I was there. I wasn't trying to eavesdrop, but our apartment isn't that big. That's when I heard her say it. He was laughing and telling her friends how I'm basically her little bitch. Like those exact words she said, I do whatever she tells me to and she's got me trained. Her friends were eating it up too, saying stuff like, good for you and make sure he Knows his place. He laughed and agreed. Then she said something that really got me. She goes, I'm not even worried about my exam tomorrow because my bitch will wake me up and probably have breakfast ready, too. I just stood there holding my water bottle feeling like an idiot. I didn't say anything. I went back to the bedroom and she came in a few minutes later acting totally normal, kissing me good night like everything was fine. I barely slept. I kept replaying it in my head. Was I really that pathetic? Did she actually see me that way or was she just trying to sound cool in front of her friends? Morning came and her alarm went off at 7. Normally I'd shake her shoulder until she woke up. Sometimes took a couple minutes. This time I just rolled over. Her alarm buzzed for like 15 minutes. She turned it off in her sleep like always. Then it went quiet. I could have woken her up. Part of me wanted to, but another part of me was just done. If I'm her little bitch, then she can wake herself up like an adult. I ended up falling back asleep when I woke up again.

I got angry that my tax refund paid off my husband's child support. My husband Jake and I filed our taxes together this year. We've been married for two years and this was our second time doing joint taxes. I was actually excited because we were supposed to get like $2,000 back. I already had plans for it. I wanted to fix the a C in my car because it's been broken since last summer and driving to work in Georgia heat is actual torture. I was also gonna finally get my laptop fixed because the screen is cracked and half the keyboard doesn't work anymore. Next day comes around and I check our bank account, $175. That's it. I literally stared at my phone for like five minutes thinking there was a mistake. I called Jake immediately and he was at work. So he sounded annoyed. I asked him what happened to our refund and he got all quiet. Then he said the state took most of it for back child support. I didn't even know he owed back child support like at all. He has a daughter from his ex girlfriend and he told me he pays $400 every month. I've seen money leave our account before, so I just believed him. Turns out he owed $7,000, that he just never mentioned $7,000. That it's not like a small, oops, I forgot to tell you thing. That's a huge deal. I felt sick, like actually nauseous. I sat in My car in the parking lot at work and just felt completely betrayed. That was my money, too. I worked all year. I paid taxes all year and it just disappeared to cover something he should have been handling all along. When I got home that night, I told him I was upset and he literally rolled his eyes at me. He said I should be happy because now the back payment is cleared and he can contribute more to our bills each month. I was like, are you serious? Right now his daughter is 14. He still has to pay child support every month until she's eighteen. It's not like this magically freed up a bunch of money. He still owes the same $400 he always did. He just got bailed out by my tax return without even asking me, without even warning me. He got mad at me for being mad. He said I was being selfish and that his daughter needed that money. I told him I'm not upset about his daughter getting support. I'm upset that he hid $7,000 of debt from me and let me think we were getting a refund when he knew the whole time it was gonna get taken. He said he didn't know for sure and that I was overreacting. I wasn't overreacting. I started looking through our bank statements after that because I didn't trust him anymore. Turns out some months he wasn't even paying the full 400 he pay Like 200 or skip it completely. And I had no idea. His ex never said anything to me about it, but I'm sure she noticed I felt so stupid. We share everything. We have a joint account. I pay half the rent and groceries and all the bills.

My parents missed my wedding to take my man child brother to Disneyland. So my grandfather stepped in to walk me down the aisle. When my father found out, he rushed back to beg for forgiveness, but I declined and publicly disowned him. For context, I'm 27F with a brother, Colton, 21 m. He's been the golden child since birth, while I basically cease to exist. My mom transformed from a loving mother into one of those boy moms you see getting roasted online. My dad still love to me, but he's always been too scared to stand up to her. They missed my ballet recitals, my high school graduation, my college graduation, all for Colton's activities. When I was 19, they told me my college fund had been used after a house fire. Years later, I found out they gave that money to Colton to buy him a car and an apartment. I had to work three jobs to pay for community college while he got everything handed to him. The only person who stood up for me was my grandpa. He lives across the country, but he always called my parents out on their treatment of me. When Sebastian proposed last year, I told my parents at dinner, and my mom literally said, that's nice without looking up from her phone. She was texting Colton about some trip they were planning. We sent formal paper invitations to everyone. I got confirmation that my parents received theirs. No response. I texted them directly asking if they got the invite left on read. I tried bringing it up in person. One time, I said, there's an important event coming up that I really need you at. And she goes, oh, honey, we can't. We're taking Colton to Disneyland that weekend. He's been so stressed with work and really needs this. I hadn't even told her the date yet. My 21 year old brother was getting a Disneyland vacation, and they were choosing that over my wedding. Not a can we reschedule? Or which date works best better, just a flat no. I gave up. I had been planning this beautiful day, talking about venues and dress shops with my aunts right in front of my mom. She'd smile, say, sounds lovely, dear, and immediately change the subject back to my wedding. Day was perfect. My grandpa flew in two days early. When he walked me down the aisle, I wasn't sad my dad wasn't there. I was grateful. Grandpa was exactly who I wanted. My aunt posted photos on Facebook with a caption like, beautiful wedding for a beautiful bride. So grateful to celebrate with family who actually shows up for the important moments. Within hours, it went viral in my parents'small town. Everyone knew they'd missed their only daughter's wedding to take their adult son to Disneyland. The comments were brutal. People they'd known for decades were asking, what kind of parents prioritize a theme park trip over their Child's wedding. My grandpa drove straight to their house. The next day, he showed up and tore into my dad. He made my dad cry, something he'd never seen in 50 years. He told him, you chose Mickey Mouse over walking your daughter down the aisle. That broke my dad. He told my mom he wanted a divorce unless she made things right with me. That's when my phone started blowing up. First came angry messages from Colton. I

My boss said I was too friendly with our biggest client. The email that would destroy my boss's career was only three sentences long. Denise called me into her office first thing that morning and she was holding a printed spreadsheet like it was evidence of a crime. She said, John's company is 40% of our revenue and you're too friendly with him. I was the top salesperson at our small company. Your personal conversations need to stop. It's unprofessional. Asking about his family. Then it clicked. Previous week our owner had praised me in front of everyone. He'd called me the heart of the sales team while Denise just stood there with her jaw clenched so tight I thought she might crack a tooth. Now I understood what this was really about. She was jealous. I try. I'd reasoning with her. John stays with us because of our relationship. He told me that himself. Her face went red. Business only from now on. That's an order. She typed furiously and sent an email to me and HR then turned her screen toward me with this triumphant look. Find this or you're fired for insubordination. I signed it knowing exactly what would happen. John's contract renewal was in three days. The very next morning, John called with pure excitement in his voice. My daughter got into her dream college. I had to tell you first, my response came out flat and robotic and I hated myself for it. How can I help you with business today. The silence that followed made my chest tight. Then came the confusion that broke my heart. Are you okay? Did something happen? I wanted to explain everything, but couldn't risk my job. I can only discuss business matters. The hurt in his voice was unmistakable. After five years, that's how you talk to me? The line went dead and I just sat there staring at my phone. Within an hour, John called Denise directly through the thin wall. I heard her cheerful response that made my blood boil. Yes, John. He's following new professional guidelines I implemented. It's how we do business now. She walked past my desk afterward with a smug smile. She said, John understands completely. But I knew John better than she ever would. That afternoon, everything shifted. John's assistant called and her voice was different, more formal. John's moving your renewal meeting to tomorrow morning. He's taking other meetings this afternoon. My heart sank because I knew those were competitor meetings. Denise overheard and her smile finally vanished. Why would he move it up, she asked. The next morning brought even worse news. Our second biggest client called Denise directly and I could hear him through the wall. John told me, you've gone corporate on us. If you're treating him like just another account number after five years, what am I? Denise's face went white as printer paper while she desperately promised we valued all our clients, but the damage Was already spreading like wildfire. The renewal meeting arrived like a funeral. John walked in and just placed a folder on the table. No handshake, no smile. I've been with you for five years. Your prices aren't the best. Your products aren't unique. I stayed because I thought we were partners, not just transactions. He looked directly at me with disappointment. Can you honestly tell me you don't care that my daughter achieved her.

I got a call from my brother at eleven PM on a Tuesday saying Mom's in the hospital. You need to come quick. It's serious. I dropped everything, drove four hours through the night, panicking the whole time, and burst into the hospital waiting room. Everyone was just sitting there calmly eating subway sandwiches. Turns out it was a family intervention they planned because I work too much and never visit anymore. My hands were still shaking from the drive. I'd run two red lights. My phone had 17 missed calls from relatives I hadn't spoken to in months. Now my brother Kevin was standing there holding a Turkey sub like nothing happened. Sit down, my mom said. She wasn't even in a hospital gown. She was wearing her church sweater. Are you kidding me right now? My aunt Linda jumped in. We're worried about you, honey. You never come home anymore. You missed Thanksgiving, you missed Kevin's engagement party. I missed those things because I was building something. I had just gotten promoted to district manager. I was finally making real money after years of living off ramen and hope. But none of them asked about that. You lied about mom dying, I said slowly. Kevin shrugged. You wouldn't have come otherwise. That part was true. But not because I didn't care. Because every time I visited, it turned into this. Me getting lectured about priorities while they lived off their spouses income or dad's old business money. My Mom started crying. The fake kind. I just want my son back. The old you actually cared about family. The old me worked at a grocery store and lived in their basement. The old me had time because I had nothing. I sat down. Not because I wanted to, but because my legs felt weird. What do you want from me? They had a whole list. Weekly dinners. Help with Kevin's wedding planning. Showing up to Mom's book club just to be present. My dad, who hadn't said a word yet, finally spoke. You think you're too good for us now? I wasn't about to cry in front of them, so I left. I walked out of that hospital, got in my car and drove home in silence. Three months went by. No calls, no texts. I sent mom flowers on her birthday. She didn't respond. Then Kevin called. Hey, man, I need a favor. Wedding venue fell through. Can you help cover part of it? Like eight grand? $8,000? The same brother who faked a medical emergency wanted eight grand? Your family, he said. Said this is what we do. I thought about it for maybe two seconds. No, he lost it. Started yelling about how selfish I was, how I changed, how money made me cold. I hung up. A week later, my mom left a voicemail. Sweet. Warm.

Then she'd divorce me, claim I was controlling and abusive and take me for everything. She tried to deny it at first, but I, I had screenshots of everything. She finally broke down and admitted it all, the affair, the pregnancy, the plan. That was the end of my two year marriage. And my family, they took her side completely. When she announced the divorce on social media and her relationship with my brother, my parents posted congratulations. He told me I should be happy they'd found each other. And Stop being so selfish, they said this was for the best. The divorce got ugly fast. My ex and her lawyer painted me as a monster, said I'd forced her to quit her job, isolated her from friends, controlled everything. My parents backed up every lie in court. They told the judge they'd cut contact with me years ago because of my misogynistic attitude and violent temper. I lost my car, lost a huge settlement, but I kept a house and I walked away with my dignity. I threw myself into work, pushed myself harder than ever, and two weeks ago, it paid off. I got promoted, significant raise, better position, company car. I was finally moving forward. I celebrated with dinner at my favorite restaurant and posted about it online. That was my second mistake. Within 24 hours, my mother started calling. I ignored her. She called more. Then she showed up at my office and refused to leave. She got into a screaming match with our receptionist. It was humiliating. I finally promised to visit just to get her to leave. A few days later, I.

Have you ever been recruited to be Santa's helper at a mall by a desperate elf? Last December, I was killing time at the mall waiting for my girlfriend to finish her shift at the jewelry store when a tiny woman in an elf costume grabbed my arm. Please, you have to help me, she whispered, her fake pointed ears drooping. Santa just quit mid shift and there are 40 kids in line. I'm 6 foot 4 with a beard I've been growing since October. She looked at me like I was the answer to her prayers. I don't know anything about being Santa, I protested. She was already dragging me toward the North Pole setup. Can you say ho, ho, ho and not swear in front of children? When I nodded, she said, you're hired. Before I could object, she shoved me into a break room where a red suit hung on a chair still warm from the previous Santa. He left because kid threw up on him, she explained, tossing me the pants. Third time this week. I should have run, but she looked so desperate and somewhere outside children were waiting. The suit was too small, the jacket barely closed. The pants ended at my calves and the beard kept sliding sideways. The elf who introduced herself as Brenda looked me over and sighed. It'll have to do. Just remember, every kid gets a candy cane. No promises about specific the gifts and absolutely no holding babies. My First kid was easy, a shy five year old who whispered she wanted a Dinosaur. I deepened my voice, said something about checking my list and sent her off with a candy cane. I thought I had this figured out. Then came Tyler. Tyler was 7, skeptical and armed with questions. Why does your beard smell like coffee, he demanded. How do you fit down chimneys if you're so fat? Before I could answer, he pulled my beard down and announced to the entire line, this isn't the real Santa. Panic spread through the crowd. Parents glared. Children started crying. Brenda looked like she might faint. That's when inspiration struck. I leaned forward and whispered loudly enough for everyone to hear. You're absolutely right, Tyler. I'm not Santa. The crowd gasped and his face went white. But I continued. I'm Santa's brother, Steve. Santa's busy at the North Pole with a massive toy emergency. A whole shipment of game consoles got delivered to the wrong warehouse. He sent me to take notes on what everyone wants while he fixes it. Tyler's eyes widened. Santa has a brother? I nodded solemnly. Someone has to run the workshop while he's delivering presents. I usually stay at the North Pole, but this is an emergency. Line of children buzzed with excitement. They'd met Santa's brother. This was even better than regular Santa. For the next three hours, I became Steve Claws. I told kids about my workshop specializing in unusual toys. I explained how I Invented the self wrapping present. One girl asked why I wasn't famous like Santa. And I said I preferred working behind the scenes. Someone has to test all those video games. I winked. Parents started taking pictures, thinking about meeting Santa's mysterious brother. Kids asked increasingly creative questions. And I made up an entire Claus family history. There was Uncle Pete who trained the reindeer, Cousin Maria who designed the Slays GPS system, and Grandma Claus who quality tested all the cookies. Around hour 4, a kid with thick glasses approach. My dad says Santa isn't real, he said quietly. The crowd went silent. This was the moment every mall Santa dreaded. I knelt down to his level. Your dad's right about something, I said. The Santa you see in stores and malls isn't the real one. But that doesn't mean the magic isn't real. Every time someone gives a gift, helps someone in need or makes someone smile during the holidays, that's Santa's magic working through them. His mom started crying. Other parents nodded a.

The owner looked horrified, but our proprietary designs, our security. The nephew had convinced him their shuttle system was military grade security against corporate espionage. Rather than argue, I created a basic Powerpoint with complicated looking diagrams. I showed him how hackers target network files but explained I could implement a directed packet exchange protocol come completely made up that would make their network more secure than shuttles. For authenticity, I included a progress bar that said Securing Node Endpoint while installing standard Windows file sharing. I renamed the network to Secure Hardened Network and change the desktop backgrounds to include a small shield icon. Next day, I demonstrated the new system where files moved through secure encrypted tunnels, regular network shares. People were amazed they could access files instantly without yelling shuttle across the room. Production speed doubled within a week. The owner was thrilled but insisted we keep two USB shuttles back up in case the secure tunnels go down. Three months later, the nephew visited and nearly had a meltdown. Seeing the network in use, he cornered me in the break room. What did you do? Those computers aren't secure. The owner overheard and proudly explained. Actually, he implemented directed packet exchange protocols much more advanced than your shuttle system. The nephew left muttering about back door vulnerabilities. A year later, I still get emails from them whenever Windows updates asking if the secure tunnels are still intact. And yes, they still keep those two backup shuttles In a locked down desk drawer just in case. Actually the craziest part, Last Christmas, the owner gave everyone in the company custom engraved USB drives with emergency shuttle team printed on them. Mine says chief tunnel officer. I keep it on my keychain as a reminder that sometimes in it. The real solution isn't fixing the technology, it's working around the humans.

He's the confident, athletic type who turns heads when he walks into a room. Me, I'm the chubby, quiet guy who's been losing his hair since 23. We're friends, but we exist in completely different worlds when it comes to dating. So when Joel asked me to be his wingman on a double date, I was surprised. He'd finally gotten somewhere with Jean, this girl he'd been chasing for weeks. Catch. Jean wanted to bring her friend Sam along. Sam was apparently new to dating and nervous, so Jean thought a double date would feel safer. Joel made it very clear what my role was. Keeps Sam entertained so he could focus on Jean. Simple enough. I agreed because I had nothing better to do on a Saturday night. Now, here's the thing about Sam. We'd crossed paths a few times at university before this. Old band shirts, stretched out hoodies, and jeans that had seen better days. I looked exactly like what I was. A guy who'd given up on trying. But this time, I figured I should at least make an effort. Not for any romantic reason, just basic respect. If someone's giving up their Saturday Evening to sit across from me. After an 18 hour hospital shift, I came home and my key didn't work. My stepmother said, pay us $26,000 and we'll let you in. Your sister needs a vacation. I just nodded and said, understood. Then I walked away. The next morning, she found a letter at the door and started screaming so loud, the neighbors came outside. There's a certain kind of tired that doesn't come from lack of sleep. It sits in your bones, behind your eyes, in that hollow space where energy used to live. That's the kind of tired I was when I pulled into the driveway at 2:00am. I've been on shift for 18 hours straight, not just filling charts. I'd done chest compressions on a 16 year old until my arms burned. I pronounced two people dead. I brought one back. I had dried stains on my sleeves and hospital antiseptic buried so deep in my skin that showers didn't help anymore. All I wanted was to laps, maybe eat something, sleep for four hours before my next shift at 7:00am. So when my key didn't fit, my brain couldn't process it. I turned it again, jiggled it, stared at the lock like it might apologize. Then the door opened. My stepmother stood there in yoga pants and a wine stain tank top holding her phone like a weapon. Oh, she said, you're back early. Behind her, my stepsister was sprawled on the couch wearing my hoodie, scrolling TikTok. Her boyfriend who hadn't Worked since moving in, was eating chips. I bought the key. Doesn't work, I said. Right. We changed the locks. Rents gone up. You want back in? $26,000 in back rent plus utilities. Your sister needs a vacation and you're a doctor. You can afford it. She said it like she was doing me a favor. I stood there holding my duffle bag, shoes sticking to the welcome mat. Did dad approve this? She smirked. Your father's overseas. This is my house. When he's gone, I make the rules. I looked past her. My textbook, we're still stacked on the floor. My name was still on the utility bills I paid two weeks ago. But sure, her house understood, I said. I nodded once, turned around and walked back to my car. I didn't slam the door, didn't yell, just drove off into the night. I slept in the hospital call room that night on a plastic mattress with a scratchy blanket that smelled like bleach. And while I slept, they celebrated. My stepsister posted about it on TikTok. Some petty caption about freeloaders learning their place got 12,000 likes. They didn't know was that I've been waiting for this moment for three years. Before my dad deployed overseas, he called me into his office, told me he knew what kind of person Lisa was, said he'd seen how she treated me when he wasn't around. Then he handed me a folder. Inside was a deed transfer, signed, notarized, legal. He put the house in my name before he left, told me not to tell Lisa, told me to keep paying the mortgage like normal, let her think she was in control and wait. I'll show you who she really is eventually, he said. And when she does, you'll know what to do. I've been paying the mortgage for three years every month on time, which meant Lisa had been paying me rent this entire time. She just didn't know it. The next morning I drove back and knocked once. Then I left an envelope on the doormat. Then I parked down the street and waited. 15 minutes later, the door opened. Lisa appeared in fuzzy slippers holding a mug that said, I want mom. She bent down, picked up the envelope, opened it and screamed. Not a gasp, a full throated soul shaking.

But somehow these bank workers never ask questions. And it was only five years later that they finally became suspicious about his uniform and reported him to the police. By then, Jeffrey had already stolen more than $90,000. After he was arrested, he was forced to pay everything back and also spent 17 days in jail. She's texted me a few times saying I'm being dramatic and that I should apologize for letting her miss her exam. So when you thought you'd be wealthy and successful, you threw me away. Now that reality hit and you're struggling, suddenly I'm the best thing that ever happened to you. I love you. I've all always loved you. I'm engaged. We're getting married in September. The words hit her like a physical blow. Two weeks later, she showed up at my workplace claiming a medical emergency. I handed her two things, a restraining order and a wedding invitation. I want you to understand that I'm not just moving on from you. I've already moved on completely. Six months later, I married my fiance. My ex wife wanted a fresh start with no dead weight. I gave her exactly that.

video_description: Part1 My wife became a doctor and celebrated by handing me divorce papers in the graduation....#reddit#redditstories#shortsaskreddit#learnontiktok#askreddit
voice_to_text: My wife became a doctor and celebrated by handing me divorce papers in the graduation parking lot. I signed them without argument and disappeared so completely that three years later, she was still searching. Eight years of working double shifts to pay her medical school tuition, eight years of frozen dinners, canceled vacations and being told once I graduate, everything will be different. The graduation ceremony was on a Thursday in may. I took the day off work, bought a new shirt. This was supposed to be our moment, our achievement, our future finally beginning. When they called her name, I stood up and clapped harder than anyone else. The ceremony ended around noon. I waited by the car while she posed with classmates. That diploma clutched like a golden ticket. When she finally walked over, I expected a hug. Instead, she handed me a vanilla envelope. Divorce papers, she said, like she was discussing the weather. I already signed my part. This wasn't a spur of the moment decision. This was planned. Look, I don't need you anymore. I have my degree, job offers, future. You were helpful during school, but that chapter is over. No dead weight. Eight years of marriage reduced to two words, helpful and dead weight. Her colleagues were gathering around us watching. I open the envelope. Everything already filled out. Assets divided, apartment claimed. Then I did something that surprised everyone. I pulled out a pen and signed every page right there in the Parking lot. I ended our marriage with the same casualness she'd started this conversation there. Congratulations on your graduation and your divorce. Her mouth drop popped open. She'd expected drama, begging anger. You're not going to fight this. Why would I fight for someone who just called me dead weight? I walked away from the car, leaving her standing there with her diploma in one hand and our signed divorce papers in the other. Three days later, I was gone from the state. The beauty of being married to someone who never paid attention to finances. She had no idea what I controlled. The apartment she thought she was getting. Lease in my name only paid for my personal account for two years. I closed our joint.

There used to be a type of contract in the NFL that literally made two teams go to war. They were called poison pill contracts and they could only be signed in very specific situations. But I think the NFL should bring these back because the story behind this is so funny. What happened was in the 2006 NFL offseason, the Seahawks placed the transition tag on future hall of Fame guard Steve Hutchinson. Now basically what that does is it makes it so that if he signs a contract anywhere else in free agency, the Seahawks have the opportunity to match. But the Vikings did something very dirty. They signed him to a contract that the Seahawks could match, but they added a clause that made the deal fully guaranteed if at any point on the contract, Hutchinson was not the highest paid offensive lineman on the team. the Seahawks had just signed Walter Jones to a record setting contract, so if the Seahawks had matched it, it would have been fully guaranteed. The Seahawks lost the hall of Famer to the Vikings, but years down the line, they got their revenge. They added a clause to receiver Nate Burleson's contract when he was given the transition tag that made the contract fully guaranteed if he had to play more than five games in the state of Minnesota. Basically saying like, you gotta pay me more if you want me to live in this crappy state.
